\h Yirmeyah
\toc1 Yirmeyah
\toc2 Yirmeyah
\toc3 Yer.
\mt1 Yirmeyah
\mt2 (Jeremiah)
\is1 Introduction
\ip The prophet Yirmeyah/Jeremiah, started his vocation as a prophet around 627 B.C. and continued for just under fifty years until around 580 B.C. Te long time of serving Yirmeyah, impanpanayan he/his the people concerning the destruction coming of nation due to sins their, and of worshipping ran of false gods. And/Now saw of Yirmeyah the katumanan of prophesied he/his of time nasakup e the Yerushalem of Nibukadnisar King of Babylon. Saw/Found his again the demolition of city and temple, and the capture of many people other of King their there to Babylon. Prophesied he/his again the return of people from capture their, and the replacement of standing up of nation there to old natahuan here.
\ip \bk The Account of Yirmeyah\bk* divided of five main sections: 1. The calling to Yirmeyah; 2. the what was said of God for of nation of Yehudah and of teachers here at time of kingdom of Husiyas, Huwakim, Hihuyakin and of Sidikiyas; 3. the all persecution of people according to it’s written of Baruk secretary of Yirmeyah, including the various prophecies, and the important what happened of life of Yirmeyah; 4. the what was said of Master God concerning the various foreigner there nations; and 5. the other still story concerning the demolition of Yerushalem, and of pegkaddakep of people going to Babylon.
\ip Merciful person Yirmeyah; very his love the his people, and disliked he/his the judging them. There are parts of document very the love his of telling concerning the sufferings he/his due to because called he of God so that to become prophets. Like fire there to heart he/his the speech of Master God, and not he/his indeed this igkeeles.
\ip Written again of this document coming the time there is e new agreement. And/Now the that agreement eg-ay-ayaran of people of God and obeyed their, even still not/none teacher thinking them because written man e this there to me heart their. (31:31-34)
\iot Main components of this document
\io1 Yirmeyah’s calling \ior 1:1-19\ior*
\io1 The prophecies concerning the kingdom of Husiyas, Huwakim, Huwakin, and of Sidikiyas \ior 2:1–25:38\ior*
\io1 Yirmeyah’s persecution \ior 26:1–45:5\ior*
\io1 The prophecies for nations \ior 46:1–51:64\ior*
\io1 Yerushalem’s destruction \ior 52:1-34\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\p
\v 1 \add These are\add* the messages from Hilkiyah’s son, Yirmeyah—one of the priests who were in Anatot in Benyamin’s territory.
\v 2 Yahweh’s messages \add started\add* coming to him when Yehudah’s King Yoshiyah \add (Josiah,\add* Amon’s son) was in the thirteenth year of his reign.\x + \xo 1:2: \xt 2Ki 22:3–23:27; 2Ch 34:8–35:19.\x*
\v 3 \add It continued\add* through the \add reign\add* of Yoshiyah’s son, King Yehoyakim \add (Jehoiakim)\add* until the end of the eleventh year of \add the reign\add* of Yoshiyah’s son, King Hizkiyah \add (Hezekiah)\add*—Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* was exiled in the fifth month \add of that year\add*.\x + \xo 1:3: a \xt 2Ki 23:36–24:7; 2Ch 36:5-8; \xo b \xt 2Ki 24:18–25:21; 2Ch 36:11-21.\x*
\s1 Yirmeyah’s calling
\q1
\v 4 \add Now\add* Yahweh’s message came to me:
\q1
\v 5 “Before I formed you in \add your mother\add*, I \add already\add* knew you,
\q1 and before you came out of the womb, I \add had a plan for you\add*.
\q1 I appointed you as a prophet to the nations.”
\p
\v 6 \add But\add* I said, “Oh no, Yahweh, my master. Listen, I don’t know how to speak, because I’m \add just\add* a young lad.”
\p
\v 7 \add but\add* Yahweh told me, “Don’t say that you’re only a child, because you must go to everyone I send you to and you must tell them everything that I command you to say.
\v 8 Don’t be afraid of them, because I’ll be with you to rescue you.”
\m That’s Yahweh’s message.
\p
\v 9 Then Yahweh stretched out his hand and touched my mouth and said, “Listen, I’ve put my messages into your mouth.
\v 10 I’m appointing you today over the nations and kingdoms—to uproot and to break down, to destroy and to pull down, to build and to plant.”
\s1 Yahweh encourages Yirmeyah
\p
\v 11 \add Another time,\add* Yahweh’s message came to me, saying, “Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add*, what do you see?”
\p “I see a branch from an almond tree,” I \add replied\add*.
\p
\v 12 Then Yahweh told me, “You’ve done well to see \add that\add*, because I keep watch\f + \fr 1:12 \ft There’s a play on words in the original here, as the Hebrew word for ‘keeping watch’ has the same consonants as the word for ‘almond’.\f* on my message \add to make sure it happens\add*.”
\p
\v 13 Then Yahweh asked me a second time what I was seeing, and I replied, “I see a pot full of boiling water and it’s tipping towards the north.”
\p
\v 14 “\add Yes,\add* disaster will come from the north \add and\add* be released onto all the inhabitants of this region,” Yahweh \add continued\add*.
\v 15 “Listen, I’m about to summon all the clans of the northern kingdoms, and they’ll come and \add attack\add* the walls around Yerushalem and all of Yehudah’s \add other\add* cities, then each \add king\add* will place his throne at the entrance to Yerushalem’s gates.” That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 16 “\add That’s how\add* I’ll judge \add my people\add* for their wickedness as they’ve abandoned me and \add sacrificed\add* to other gods and bowed down to \add idols\add* that they made with their own hands.
\v 17 \add So\add* \add Yirmeyah\add*, \add get yourself ready and go\add* and tell them everything that I’ll tell you. Don’t be scared \add in front of them\add* or else I’ll scare you \add right there\add* \add in front of them\add*!
\v 18 And listen, today I’ve you \add as strong as\add* a fortified city and an iron pillar and bronze walls, as far as the kings of Yehudah \add are concerned\add*, along with their officials and priests, and the \add general population\add*.
\v 19 They’ll \add oppose\add* you \add but\add* they won’t \add be able to\add* defeat you because I’ll be with you to rescue you,” says Yahweh.
\c 2
\s1 Yisrael has deviated from Yahweh
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh \add gave\add* me a message
\v 2 to proclaim to Yerushalem’s ears:
\q1 “Yahweh says: I remember your loyal commitment \add when you were all young\add*
\q1 and your love \add when you were committed to me\add*.
\q1 You all followed after me in the wilderness \add where no crops were planted\add*.
\q1
\v 3 Yisrael was set apart for Yahweh—the firstfruits of his harvest.
\q1 All those who devoured it became guilty—calamity came to them.
\q1 That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Yisrael’s ancestors turned away
\p
\v 4 Listen to Yahweh’s message you \add descendants\add* of Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 and all you clans \add that are part\add* of Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Yahweh asks: what injustices did you ancestors find in me,
\q1 that \add caused them\add* to become distant from me.
\q1 They \add chased\add* after vanity and became vain.
\q1
\v 6 They didn’t \add try to find out\add* where Yahweh was—
\q1 \add the one\add* brought led them out of Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*
\q1 then led them \add through\add* the wilderness with its pits and desert areas.
\q1 \add It was\add* a \add region\add* of deep darkness \add without water\add*—
\q1 an \add area\add* that no one passes through, \add let alone\add* lives in.
\q1
\v 7 Then I took you to the Carmel \add region\add*
\q1 to eat its fruit and \add other\add* good things.
\q1 \add However\add* you came and defiled my land
\q1 and made the inheritance \add that I gave you\add* into \add something detestable\add*.
\q1
\v 8 The priests didn’t ask where Yahweh was,
\q1 and the handlers of the law didn’t know me.
\q1 The shepherds rebelled against me,
\q1 and the prophets prophesied by Ba’al
\q1 and they went after \add things\add* that wouldn’t profit them.
\s1 Yahweh’s case against his people
\q1
\v 9 Yahweh declares: I will bring a case against you all,
\q1 and I’ll contend against your \add children and\add* your grandchildren.
\q1
\v 10 If you all cross over \add west\add* to the coasts of Cypress \add island\add* and look,
\q1 or head \add east\add* to Kedar, \add ask around\add* and \add pay careful attention\add*
\q1 to see if something like this has \add ever\add* happened \add before\add*.
\q1
\v 11 Has a country ever \add swapped out\add* its gods (not that they were \add actual\add* gods)?
\q1 \add But\add* my people have exchanged their \add greatness\add* for something \add of no benefit\add*.
\q1
\v 12 \add You\add* heavens, be appalled and shudder.
\q1 Become \add utterly\add* desolate.
\q1 \add That’s what Yahweh says\add*
\q1
\v 13 because my people have done two evil things:
\q1 1. They’ve abandoned the spring of living water
\q1 \add and 2. They’ve gone and\add* dug wells for themselves—broken cisterns that can’t hold any water.
\s1 Yisrael’s punishment for abandonment
\q1
\v 14 Is Yisrael a slave? Was it born \add into slavery\add*?
\q1 Why has it \add been carried off as\add* plunder?
\q1
\v 15 Young lions roared at it—
\q1 they’ve \add made their voice heard\add*.
\q1 They’ve made the land into wasteland—
\q1 its cities have become ruins without any inhabitants.
\q1
\v 16 Also the people from Memphis \add (Heb. Nof)\add* and Tahpanhes have shaved your \add heads\add*.
\q1
\v 17 Didn’t you \add bring\add* this on yourself by abandoning your god, Yahweh
\q1 at the time when he was leading you along \add the right\add* path.
\q1
\v 18 \add So\add* now, \add what’s the point of\add* travelling to Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* to drink from Shihor’s waters?
\q1 And \add why bother\add* \add taking a trip\add* to Assyria \add (Heb. Ashshur)\add* to drink the river water?
\q1
\v 19 Your \add own\add* wickedness will punish you
\q1 and your turning away will rebuke you.
\q1 \add So\add* see and know that it’s evil and bitter to abandon your god Yahweh,
\q1 and you no longer have \add respect\add* for me.
\m That’s Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Yisrael refuses to worship Yahweh
\q1
\v 20 I broke off your yoke from long ago.
\q1 I tore your chains to pieces and you said that you wouldn’t \add disobey\add*,
\q1 because you’d been lying down with prostitutes on every high hill and under every leafy tree.
\q1
\v 21 I myself had planted you as a choice vine from a reliable seed,
\q1 \add but\add* how you’ve changed yourself into some degenerate, wild vine,
\q1
\v 22 because even if you wash yourself with \add bleach\add* or use \add heaps of\add* soap,
\q1 your guilt \add remains\add* as a stain \add in front of\add* me.
\m That is the declaration of my master, Yahweh.
\q1
\v 23 How can you say, ‘I’m not defiled—I haven’t \add worshipped\add* the Baals’?
\q1 Consider your conduct in the valley.
\q1 Recognise what you’ve done:
\q1 \add behaving like\add* a young, female camel \add that flits here and there\add*.
\q1
\v 24 \add You’re like\add* a wild, female donkey, accustomed to the wilderness in its desire for the wind.
\q1 No one can hold her back when she’s in heat.
\q1 All those searching for her won’t give up trying to find her \add at mating time\add*.
\q1
\v 25 Keep your feet from becoming bare, and your throat from thirst,
\q1 \add but\add* you’ve said that it’s hopeless,
\q1 as you love foreign gods and \add feel obliged to follow\add* them.
\s1 Yisrael deserves their punishment
\p
\v 26 It’s like the shame \add felt\add* by a thief who gets \add caught\add*.
\q1 So \add too,\add* \add you\add* \add Israelis\add* will be shamed:
\q1 \add the people\add*, their kings and officials, and their priests and prophets
\q1
\v 27 who say to the tree, ‘You’re my father,’
\q1 and to the \add standing\add* stone, ‘You gave birth to me.’
\q1 \add Yes,\add* they \add show their backs\add* to me, not their faces,
\q1 \add but\add* \add when calamity comes\add*, they’ll say, ‘\add Do something\add* and rescue us!’
\b
\q1
\v 28 \add So\add* where \add then\add* are the gods that you made for yourself?
\q1 Let them \add take action\add* if they can save you at the time of your calamity,
\q1 because you \add have as many gods and you have cities in\add* Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*.
\q1
\v 29 Why do you all \add complain\add* to me, \add when\add* all of you have rebelled against me?
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 30 \add It was a waste of time when I beat\add* your sons—they wouldn’t accept discipline.
\q1 You’ve all \add killed\add* your prophets like a destructive lion.
\q1
\v 31 \add You in this\add* generation, pay attention to Yahweh’s message.
\q1 Have I been a wilderness to Yisrael, or a land of thick darkness?
\q1 Why would my people say that they’ve now gone their own ways
\q1 \add and so\add* won’t come back to me again?
\q1
\v 32 Would a young woman forget \add to wear\add* her \add jewelry\add*,
\q1 or a bride \add forget to wear\add* her \add wedding\add* sashes?
\q1 \add However\add* my people have forgotten me for \add such a long time\add*.
\q1
\v 33 You’ve \add become very good\add* at finding love—
\q1 you \add could\add* even teach \add prostitutes\add* \add a thing or two\add*!
\q1
\v 34 The blood of innocent, poor \add people\add* was even found on your \add clothes\add*—
\q1 it wasn’t because you \add caught\add* them breaking in, but you did it anyway
\q1
\v 35 then you said, ‘But I’m innocent—surely \add he’s not angry at\add* me.’
\q1 Listen, I’m about to judge you because you said that you didn’t sin.
\q1
\v 36 Why are you \add constantly\add* changing your \add alliances\add*?
\q1 You’ll be disappointed by Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* just like you were disappointed by Assyria \add (Heb. Ashshur)\add*.
\q1
\v 37 \add What’s more\add*, you’ll \add be removed\add* from this \add place\add* will your hands on your head,
\q1 because Yahweh has rejected the \add ones\add* \add that you put your confidence in\add*
\q1 →and \add they won’t be of any help to\add* you.
\c 3
\s1 Yisrael is unfaithful
\s4 Northern kingdom
\p
\v 1 Listen, if a man \add divorced\add* his wife and she left \add and married\add* another man,
\q1 surely he wouldn’t \add move in with\add* her again?
\q1 Wouldn’t the \add country\add* \add end up totally immoral\add*?
\q1 \add Now\add* you’ve acted like a prostitute with many \add partners\add*—
\q1 would you then return to me?
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 2 Look up at the \add barren hilltops\add* and see.
\q1 Is there anywhere \add there\add* where you haven’t \add given yourself\add*?
\q1 You sat by the paths \add waiting\add* for them like an Arab \add waiting\add* in the wilderness,
\q1 and \add so\add* you’ve polluted the \add nation\add* by your \add acts of\add* prostitution and wickedness.
\q1
\v 3 \add That’s why\add* the showers have been withheld
\q1 and the late rains never came,
\q1 \add yet\add* you \add have the look of\add* a prostitute who refuses to be ashamed.
\b
\q1
\v 4 Even now you \add say\add* that I’m your father,
\q1 \add or that\add* I’m your close friend from \add since you were young\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Will he \add be angry\add* forever?
\q1 Or permanently keep watch?
\q1 Listen, you say \add that\add*, but you do \add all\add* the wicked things that you can.
\s1 Yehudah is also unfaithful
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 6 \add At the time when\add* Yoshiyah \add (Josiah)\add* was king \add of Yehudah (Judah)\add*, Yahweh asked me, “Do you see what \add faithless\add* Yisrael has done? She herself has walked up every high hill, and has been a prostitute underneath every green tree.\x + \xo 3:6: \xt 2Ki 22:1–23:30; 2Ch 34:1–35:27.\x*
\v 7 \add However\add* I thought that after she’d done all those \add things\add*, she’d return to me, \add but\add* she hasn’t, and her treacherous sister, Yehudah, saw \add her\add*.
\v 8 \add So\add* I saw that because of all those situations where \add faithless\add* Yisrael had committed adultery, I had given her divorce \add notice\add* to her and sent her away. \add But\add* her sister Yehudah, acting treacherously, \add wasn’t worried\add* and she went out and also prostituted herself.
\v 9 \add Because she took her prostitution lightly\add*, the \add nation became immoral\add* and committed adultery with \add standing\add* stones and trees.
\v 10 Then \add after\add* all that, that treacherous sister Yehudah didn’t return to me \add with sincerity\add*, \add but\add* with deception. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Hope for unfaithful Yisrael
\s4 Northern kingdom
\p
\v 11 Then Yahweh told me: \add Unfaithful\add* Yisrael has \add actually\add* been more upright than treacherous Yehudah!
\v 12 Go up north and tell \add them\add*:
\q1 \add Unfaithful\add* Yisrael, Yahweh declares:
\q1 Return \add to me\add*—
\q1 I won’t \add continue to be angry at\add* you, because I’m faithful.
\m That’s Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 13 \add However\add* you must recognise your disobedience
\q1 because you’ve rebelled against your god, Yahweh,
\q1 and you’ve \add extended your connections\add* to foreign \add gods\add* under every leafy tree,
\q1 and you haven’t listened to my voice.
\m That’s Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 14 Return \add you\add* \add unfaithful children\add*, Yahweh declares,
\q1 because I’m your husband.
\q1 Then I’ll take you all—one from a city and a \add couple\add* from a clan—and I’ll bring you to Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*,
\q1
\v 15 and I’ll give you shepherds \add who’ll be faithful to me\add*,
\q1 and they will \add guide\add* you with knowledge and insight.
\q1
\v 16 Then when you’re fruitful and multiply in the land, Yahweh says,
\q1 they’ll no longer talk about having the chest \add containing\add* Yahweh’s agreement.
\q1 They won’t call it to mind or remember it,
\q1 and they won’t miss it or want a new one made again.
\q1
\v 17 At that time, they’ll call Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* Yahweh’s throne,
\q1 and they’ll be gathered \add there\add* from all the nations \add to honour\add* Yahweh’s name,
\q1 and they won’t want to \add behave\add* again according to the evil in their own stubborn \add minds\add*.
\q1
\v 18 In those days, the people of Yehudah will \add join\add* the people of Yisrael,
\q1 coming from the northern \add lands\add* to the land that I gave your ancestors as an inheritance.
\s1 The sinning of Yisrael
\q1
\v 19 Then I thought to myself \add about\add* how I’d accept you \add to be my children\add*,
\q1 and give you a desirable land—an inheritance that all nations \add consider very beautiful\add*.
\q1 I \add decided\add* that you’ll all call me ‘my father’,
\q1 and then you all won’t turn away from me.
\q1
\v 20 However, like a woman who deals treacherously with her companion,
\q1 so too you’ve all dealt treacherously with me, \add you\add* \add Israeli people\add*.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\b
\q1
\v 21 A sound of weeping is heard on the barren hilltops—
\q1 the \add Israeli people begging for mercy\add*
\q1 because they’ve followed paths of \add disobedience\add*
\q1 and they’ve forgotten their god, Yahweh.
\q1
\v 22 Come back, \add you\add* \add unfaithful children\add*—I will cure your \add faithlessness\add*.
\q1 \add Say,\add* look, we’re coming back to you because you’re our god, Yahweh.
\q1
\v 23 Deception definitely comes from the hills—a commotion of mountains.
\q1 Our god Yahweh is certainly Yisrael’s salvation.
\q1
\v 24 From our youth, \add that\add* shameful \add idol worship\add* has consumed our ancestors’ \add hard\add* work—
\q1 their sheep and cattle, and their sons and daughters.
\q1
\v 25 Let us lie down in our shame, and let our humiliation cover us,
\q1 because we’ve \add disobeyed\add* our god, Yahweh.
\q1 Our ancestors and \add then\add* we ourselves, haven’t listened to the voice of our god, Yahweh.
\c 4
\s1 A call to turn back
\p
\v 1 Yahweh says:
\q1 If you’ll return, Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*,
\q1 \add yes,\add* if you’ll return to me
\q1 and remove \add those\add* detestable \add idols\add* \add away from me\add* without wavering,
\q1
\v 2 and if you promise \add as Yahweh lives\add*, in truth, justice, and righteousness,
\q1 then the nations will bless themselves in him,
\q1 and \add it’s him that they’ll boast about\add*.
\p
\v 3 \add Yes,\add* tells the \add people\add* from Yerushalem and \add across all\add* Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*:
\q1 Plough your unploughed ground, \add but\add* don’t sow thornbushes.\x + \xo 4:3: \xt Hos 10:12.\x*
\q1
\v 4 Circumcise yourselves to Yahweh \add by\add* removing the foreskins from your \add hearts\add*
\q1 \add you\add* \add people\add* of Yerushalem and Yehudah,
\q1 so that my rage doesn’t \add burst out\add* and burn like fire,
\q1 \add because\add* there wouldn’t be anyone to extinguish it \add due\add* to the wickedness of your \add behaviour\add*.
\s1 The coming punishment of Yehudah
\p
\v 5 Announce in Yerushalem and declare in Yehudah to blow the horn in the land.
\q1 Call out \add loudly\add* to gather together and enter the fortified cities.
\q1
\v 6 Lift up a banner towards Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add* and \add get\add* to safety.
\q1 Don’t stand still because I’m about to bring calamity from the north \add with horrific\add* destruction.
\q1
\v 7 A lion has come up from its thicket,
\q1 and a destroyer of nations has set out.
\q1 He’s come out from his place to make your \add country\add* into a wasteland.
\q1 Your cities will be \add reduced to\add* ruins with no inhabitants.
\q1
\v 8 \add So put on\add* sackcloth—mourn and wail
\q1 because Yahweh’s burning anger hasn’t turned away from us.
\p
\v 9 Yahweh says that \add at that time\add*,
\q1 the king and his officials will \add lose\add* heart
\q1 and the priests and prophets will be astonished.
\p
\v 10 Then I \add replied\add*, “\add Oh now\add*! My master Yahweh,
\q1 you’ve certainly completely deceived Yerushalem and \add also\add* this people,
\q1 saying, ‘It will be well for you all.’ Yet the sword will \add come for our\add* throats.”
\p
\v 11 \add When that happens\add*, Yerushalem and this people will be told:
\q1 A scorching wind will come from the bare hills in the wilderness.
\q1 It won’t be coming \add just\add* to winnow \add the grain\add* and \add blow away\add* \add the chaff\add*—
\q1
\v 12 it’ll be a \add strong blast\add* from me.
\q1 \add Then\add* I’ll speak judgements \add against\add* them.
\q1
\v 13 Listen, he goes up like the clouds,
\q1 and his chariots are like the storm wind.
\q1 His horses are faster than eagles.
\q1 →\add We won’t end well\add* because we’ll be devastated.
\q1
\v 14 Yerushalem, wash the evil from your heart so that you can be saved.
\q1 \add How much longer will you hold onto\add* your wicked thoughts for,
\q1
\v 15 because a voice from Dan declares \add trouble\add*
\q1 and disaster is proclaimed from Efrayim’s hill?
\q1
\v 16 \add Remind\add* the nations—
\q1 listen, announce to Yerushalem:
\q1 They’re coming from a distant land \add to lay siege\add* \add against you\add*,
\q1 and they \add raise\add* their voice \add against\add* Yehudah’s cities.
\q1
\v 17 They’ll \add surround\add* \add Yerushalem\add* like the watchmen around a field because it rebelled against me.
\m That’s Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 18 Your conduct and your actions have brought that to you, \add Yerushalem\add*.
\q1 That’s your punishment—it’s bitter and it’ll \add pierce\add* to your heart.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s sorrow for the country
\p
\v 19 My inward parts, my \add insides\add*!
\q1 I writhe \add with chest pains\add*.
\q1 My heart is \add pounding\add*—I won’t stay silent,
\q1 →because my soul, you hear the sound of the trumpet—an alarm for battle.
\q1
\v 20 Destruction \add followed by more\add* destruction has been proclaimed,
\q1 because all the land has been devastated.
\q1 Suddenly my tents are devastated—
\q1 my tent fabrics \add gone\add* in a moment.
\q1
\v 21 How long do I have to watch \add the enemy’s\add* banner for?
\q1 How long will that trumpet sound go on for?
\q1
\v 22 \add Yes,\add* my people are foolish—they don’t know me.
\q1 They’re like stupid children who don’t understand anything.
\q1 They’ve \add very clever\add* at \add doing what’s\add* evil
\q1 and they don’t know how to do what’s good.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s vision about destruction
\q1
\v 23 I saw the land, and wow, it was formless and empty,
\q1 and the skies didn’t have any light.
\q1
\v 24 I saw the mountains, and wow, they were quaking,
\q1 and all the hills shook back-and-forth.
\q1
\v 25 I looked, and wow, there were no more \add people\add*,
\q1 and all the birds had flown away.
\q1
\v 26 I saw, and wow, the orchard had turned into a wilderness,
\q1 and all the cities had been pulled down \add out of Yahweh’s sight\add*
\q1 \add due to\add* his burning anger,
\p
\v 27 because Yahweh says this:
\q1 \add The entire country\add* will become desolate,
\q1 ^\add but\add* I won’t completely destroy it.
\q1
\v 28 The land will mourn \add after that\add*,
\q1 and the skies will darken from above,
\q1 because I’ve \add revealed my resolution\add*,
\q1 ^and I won’t \add change my mind\add* or turn back from it.
\q1
\v 29 The city people will flee from the sound of \add approaching\add* horsemen and archers.
\q1 They’ll \add head\add* into the thickets and up onto the \add cliffs\add*.
\q1 →Every city will be abandoned without anyone living in them.
\q1
\v 30 \add So\add* you,\f + \fr 4:30 \ft The Hebrew has a female \fq you \ft pronoun (as used for the city), which doesn’t match the male form of \fq devastated\ft . Many modern versions have \fqa What will you do, devastated one? \ft despite the gender mismatch.\f* what will you do \add for\add* the devastated \add one\add*?
\q1 You dress in scarlet, adorning yourself with gold jewelry.
\q1 You \add make your eyes look bigger with makeup\add*, but it won’t help—
\q1 your lovers reject you \add and\add* they’re \add coming for\add* your life.
\q1
\v 31 \add Yes,\add* I hear a sound like a woman in labour—
\q1 distress like a woman giving birth to her first child—
\q1 the sound of Tsiyyon’s daughter \add as\add* she gasps for breath.
\q1 She spreads out her hands \add saying\add*,
\q1 ‘I fear for my life because \add of those\add* murderers.’
\c 5
\s1 Yerushalem’s corruption
\q1
\v 1 Roam around Yerushalem’s streets and look and observe,
\q1 and search around its plazas.
\q1 If you can find \add one\add* person there who \add values\add* justice and \add strives to be faithful\add*,
\q1 then I’ll forgive \add the city\add*.
\q1
\v 2 Even when \add they make an oath in Yahweh’s name\add*,
\q1 it’ll \add still\add* be a lie.
\q1
\v 3 Yahweh, don’t you look for \add honesty\add*?
\q1 You struck them \add but\add* they don’t \add even react\add*.
\q1 You brought them to an end, \add but\add* they refuse to accept correction.
\q1 They make their faces harder than rock \add and\add* refuse to \add change\add*.
\q1
\v 4 Then I thought that \add maybe\add* they’re just poor \add people\add*?
\q1 They act foolishly because \add they’re not educated about\add* Yahweh’s way
\q2 or what their god \add requires of them\add*?
\q1
\v 5 \add So\add* I’ll go to the leaders and speak to them,
\q1 because they know Yahweh’s way and what their god \add requires\add*.
\q1 However, all of them have broken out from under \add his\add* yoke,
\q2 and torn off the chains.
\q1
\v 6 \add Because of that,\add* a lion from a thicket will attack them.
\q1 A wolf from the wilderness will devastate them.
\q1 A leopard lies in wait \add outside\add* their cities—
\q1 →everyone who goes out from them will be torn to pieces
\q1 because their \add disobedience is extensive\add*
\q1 and their \add disloyalty is substantial\add*.
\q1
\v 7 How could I forgive you for that?
\q1 Your children have abandoned me and have made oaths by \add things that are\add* not gods.
\q1 I satisfied them, \add but\add* they committed adultery
\q1 and \add ritually\add* cut themselves\f + \fr 5:7 \ft Many translations follow the Septuagint here rather than the Hebrew, and end up with something like \fqa gathered together\ft . (Of course, \fq the prostitute \ft here refers to idol worship.)\f* at the prostitute’s house.
\q1
\v 8 They were well-fed, lusty horses,
\q1 each man neighing at his neighbour’s wife.
\p
\v 9 Yahweh \add asks\add*:
\q1 Shouldn’t I punish them for these things?
\q1 Shouldn’t I avenge myself on a nation like that?
\q1
\v 10 Go along the rows \add in the vineyard\add* and destroy them,
\q1 \add but\add* don’t \add completely destroy them\add*—
\q1 break off their shoots because they don’t belong to Yahweh.
\q1
\v 11 \add No,\add* Yisrael’s and Yehudah’s \add people\add* had indeed dealt treacherously with me.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Yahweh rejects Yisrael
\p
\v 12 They’ve denied Yahweh and said:
\q1 He \add doesn’t exist\add* and \add nothing bad\add* will happen us,
\q1 and we’ll \add never experience\add* war or famine.
\q1
\v 13 The prophets are \add full of air\add* and \add don’t have any\add* message.
\q1 So let what they say, happen to them.
\p
\v 14 So Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 Because you’ve spoken those \add words\add*,
\q1 I’ll put my messages in your mouth as a fire
\q1 and this people \add group\add* will be the wood that it consumes.
\q1
\v 15 Listen \add you Israelis\add* to Yahweh’s declaration:
\q1 I’m about to bring to you all a nation from far away—
\q1 it’s an enduring nation that’s \add been around for a long time\add*.
\q1 You won’t know their language or understand what they say.
\q1
\v 16 Its quiver is like an open tomb.
\q1 All of them are warriors.
\q1
\v 17 It will consume your \add grain and your food\add*.
\q1 They’ll devour your sons and daughters, and your flocks and your \add cattle\add*.
\q1 They’ll \add strip\add* your grapevines and your fig trees.
\q1 With \add their\add* \add swords\add*, they’ll shatter your fortified cities that you were trusting in.
\p
\v 18 \add But\add* Yahweh says:
\q1 Even in those days, I won’t \add completely destroy\add* you all.
\q1
\v 19 When the people \add ask why\add* Yahweh’s doing that, you’ll tell them:
\q1 You rejected me and served foreign gods in your own \add country\add*,
\q1 so you’ll all serve strangers in a land that doesn’t belong to you.
\s1 Yahweh warns his people
\p
\v 20 Declare this to Yakov’s \add (Jacob’s)\add* descendants,
\q1 and proclaim it in Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*:
\q1
\v 21 Please listen to this, \add you\add* foolish, heartless people.
\q1 They have eyes \add but\add* do not see,
\q1 and they have ears, \add but\add* do not hear.\x + \xo 5:21: \xt Isa 6:9-10; Eze 12:2; Mrk 8:18.\x*
\q1
\v 22 Yahweh declares:
\q1 Should you all \add respect and strive to obey\add* me,
\q1 and shouldn’t you tremble \add in front of\add* me?
\q1 It was me who designated the sand as the boundary for the ocean—
\q1 it’s a permanent \add line\add* and the sea doesn’t go past it.
\q1 \add The waters\add* surge but get no further,
\q1 and the waves roar, but can’t get past it.\x + \xo 5:22: \xt Yob 38:8-11.\x*
\q1
\v 23 But this group of people has a stubborn and rebellious heart.
\q1 They’ve turned aside and gone away.
\q1
\v 24 They don’t say to themselves:
\q1 Please, let’s \add strive to obey\add* our god Yahweh—
\q1 the one who gives the \add autumn and spring\add* rains at the appropriate time.
\q1 He \add decides on\add* the harvest weeks for us.
\q1
\v 25 Your \add disobedience\add* has diverted those \add things\add*,
\q1 and your sins have withheld goodness from you all
\q1
\v 26 because there are wicked \add influencers\add* among my people.
\q1 They lie in wait like a bird-catcher.
\q1 They set a trap \add and\add* catch people.
\q1
\v 27 Their homes are full of deceit like a cage full of birds.
\q1 →so that’s how they’ve become \add rich and powerful\add*.
\q1
\v 28 They’ve become fat and \add slick\add*.
\q1 They also \add disobey by doing evil\add*.
\q1 They don’t plead the cause of \add those who are\add* fatherless,
\q1 and \add they’re successful, yet\add* they haven’t \add insisted\add* on justice for the poor.
\p
\v 29 Yahweh says:
\q1 Why shouldn’t I punish them \add for all that behaviour\add*?
\q1 Why shouldn’t I avenge myself on a nation like this one?
\q1
\v 30 Something horrible and shocking has happened in the \add country\add*:
\q1
\v 31 The prophets prophesy with lies,
\q1 and the priests rule \add by their own authority\add*,
\q1 and my people love it this \add way\add*,
\q1 \add but\add* what will you all do \add when it comes to its\add* end?
\c 6
\s1 Yerushalem’s last warning
\p
\v 1 Get out of Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* \add and get\add* yourselves to safety, \add you\add* people of Benyamin,
\q1 and blow a trumpet in Tekoa.
\q1 \add Send up a signal from\add* Beyt-Hakkerem
\q1 because disaster and terrible destruction looms from the north.
\q1
\v 2 Although it’s beautiful and delicate,
\q1 I \add will destroy\add* Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* daughter.
\q1
\v 3 Shepherds and their flocks will go and pitch their tents all around it.\f + \fr 6:3 \ft Many English translations interpret these ‘shepherds’ with their ‘flocks’ to be leaders of foreign nations with their armies implementing the destruction mentioned in the previous verse, i.e., the ones battling in the next verse. However, we’ve chosen to interpret the flocks grazing the city surrounds as the follow-on \+em after\+em* the destruction, before the next verse goes \+em back in time\+em* to give more details of how the destruction will occur.\f*
\q1 Each one will graze \add their own area\add*.
\p
\v 4 \add Prepare\add* for battle.
\q1 \add Take action\add* and let’s \add attack\add* at midday.
\q1 \add It won’t be good for\add* us if the day \add is ending\add*
\q1 because the evening shadows get longer.
\q1
\v 5 \add Take action\add* and \add attack\add* at night
\q1 and destroy its palaces.
\q1
\v 6 Commander-in-chief Yahweh says:
\q1 Cut down \add trees for\add* timber
\q1 and mound up a \add ramp\add* against Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*.
\q1 →That city must be \add punished\add* as it’s \add full of\add* oppression.
\q1
\v 7 Just as a well keeps its water fresh,
\q1 so too she keeps her evil fresh.
\q1 Violence and oppression can be heard \add there\add*.
\q1 I always \add see\add* sickness and plague.
\q1
\v 8 \add Take note of my warning\add* Yerushalem
\q1 in case I \add turn away\add* from you—
\q1 in case I make you desolate—
\q1 a land that’s not inhabited.
\s1 Yisrael’s disobedience
\p
\v 9 Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 \add Those who remain\add* in Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*
\q1 \add will be picked over\add* like gleaning \add the last few grapes off\add* a vine.
\q1 Return your hand over the branches like a grape-picker.
\q1
\v 10 Who should I speak to and warn so they can list?
\q1 Wow, their ears \add are so closed\add* that they can’t pay attention.
\q1 Wow, Yahweh’s message has become \add offensive\add* to them—
\q1 they don’t enjoy \add hearing\add* it.
\q1
\v 11 \add Now\add* I’m filled with Yahweh’s rage.
\q1 I’m tired of holding it in.
\p Pour it out on the children in the street
\q1 and on the young men who gather together,
\q1 because a husband will be captured with \add his\add* wife—
\q1 the \add very elderly\add* as well.
\q1
\v 12 Then their houses will be turned over to others,
\q1 \add along with their\add* fields and wives
\q1 because I’ll stretch out my hand
\q1 against the land’s inhabitants.
\m That’s Yahweh’s declaration
\q1
\v 13 because from the smallest to the greatest,
\q1 they’re all greedy for dishonest gain.
\q1 From a prophet to the priest, everyone \add deals in lies\add*.
\q1
\v 14 They’ve lightly bandaged my peoples’s wound
\q1 by saying, ‘Peace, peace,’ but there wasn’t \add any\add* peace.\x + \xo 6:14: \xt Eze 13:10.\x*
\q1
\v 15 Were they ashamed when they did something disgusting?\x + \xo 6:12-15: \xt Jer 8:10-12.\x*
\q1 \add No,\add* they weren’t ashamed—
\q1 they didn’t even know how to be humiliated
\q1 so therefore they’ll fall among the fallen.
\q1 At the time when I punish them, they’ll stumble.
\m \add That’s what\add* Yahweh says.
\s1 Yisrael rejects Yahweh’s messages
\p
\v 16 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Stand at the \add cross\add*roads and look,
\q1 and ask about the ancient paths.
\q1 ‘Where is the path of the good?’ Then walk along it
\q1 and find rest for your spirit.
\p \add But\add* they say, ‘We won’t walk \add on it\add*.’
\p
\v 17 I set watchmen over you.
\q1 Pay attention to the sound of the trumpet,
\q1 \add But\add* they said, ‘We won’t pay attention.’
\p
\v 18 Therefore listen \add you\add* nations,
\q1 and \add you\add* congregation, know \add what will happen to\add* them.
\q1
\v 19 Listen, \add you\add* earth.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* I will bring disaster to this people—
\q1 the fruit of their own plans
\q1 because they paid no attention to my messages
\q1 and they rejected my instructions.
\q1
\v 20 What \add difference does it make\add* to me if they burn frankincense that came from Sheva?
\q1 \add Or\add* \add if they have\add* good cane from a distant land?
\q1 Your burnt offerings aren’t acceptable,
\q1 and your sacrifices \add don’t please\add* me.
\q1
\v 21 So Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, I’ll give this \add group of\add* people a stumbling block,
\q1 and they’ll trip over it—
\q1 fathers and sons together,
\q1 \add both\add* a neighbour and his friend.
\s1 The coming, northern army
\p
\v 22 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, \add an army\add* is about to come from a northern country,
\q1 and a powerful nation will be roused from the remotest parts of the \add world\add*.
\q1
\v 23 They \add carry\add* bows and spears.
\q1 It’s cruel and they have no mercy.
\q1 \add They make a noise like the sea roaring\add*
\q1 and they ride \add in battle formation\add* on horses
\q1 against you, Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* daughter.
\p
\v 24 \add We felt weak when\add* we heard the reports about them.
\q1 Distress took hold of us and we’re in agony like \add a woman\add* about to give birth.
\q1
\v 25 Don’t go out to the countryside,
\q1 and don’t walk on the road
\q1 because of the enemy’s sword.
\q1 There’s terror all around.
\p
\v 26 My people’s daughter, dress yourself in sackcloth
\q1 and roll in ashes.
\q1 Go into mourning as if \add you’d lost\add* an only \add child\add*—
\q1 \add a time\add* of bitter wailing
\q1 because the destroyer will suddenly come \add against\add* us.
\q1
\v 27 I’ve appointed you to examine my people like \add ore\add*,
\q1 so you can observe their conduct, and test \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 28 They’re all stubborn rebels who go around slandering \add others\add*.
\q1 They’re all \add like\add* bronze and iron, behaving corruptly.
\q1
\v 29 The bellows \add fan\add* the fire
\q1 \add but after\add* the thorough refining, the lead \add remains\add*.
\q1 The evil \add people\add* haven’t been separated out.
\q1
\v 30 They’ll be called ‘rejected silver’
\q1 because Yahweh has rejected them.
\c 7
\s1 Yirmeyah’s preaching in the temple
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 1 Yahweh’s message came to Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add*:
\q1
\v 2 Stand at the gate at Yahweh’s \add temple\add* and proclaim this message, saying:
\q1 Listen to Yahweh’s message,
\q1 all you \add people of\add* Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* who enter these gates to worship Yahweh.
\q1
\v 3 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says that
\q1 you all must improve your ways,
\q1 and make them right
\q1 so that I’ll \add allow\add* you all to live in this \add land\add*.
\q1
\v 4 Don’t trust in deceptive words that say,
\q1 ‘Yahweh’s temple \add is here\add*.’
\q1 ‘Yahweh’s temple, Yahweh’s temple.’
\p
\v 5 \add Yes,\add* if you all really make your \add behaviour\add* good,
\q1 and everyone really \add acts fairly towards their neighbours\add*,
\q1
\v 6 \add and\add* you all don’t oppress strangers, orphans, or widows,
\q1 and don’t shed innocent blood in this place
\q1 \add or follow after\add* other gods that will harm you,
\q1
\v 7 then I’ll \add allow\add* you all to live in this place in the land that I gave to your ancestors from \add ancient times\add* and \add for the future to come\add*.
\p
\v 8 \add Listen\add*, you’re all relying on deceptive messages which can’t profit.
\v 9 Will you all \add keep\add* stealing and murdering, committing adultery and \add telling lies in court\add*, \add offering incense\add* to Baal and \add following\add* other gods that you didn’t previously know.
\v 10 Then you all come \add here\add* and stand in front of this \add temple\add* that’s \add associated with\add* my name, and say that you’re saved while you all \add continue to\add* do all those disgusting \add things\add*.
\v 11 This house which \add bears\add* my name has become a robbers’ den in your eyes. \add Listen\add*, I’ve also seen \add it\add*. That is Yahweh’s utterance.\x + \xo 7:11: \xt Mat 21:13; Mrk 11:17; Luk 19:46.\x*
\v 12 \add But\add* please go to my place in Shiloh where I had previously \add had my tent and\add* my name resided, and see what I did to \add destroy\add* \add that place\add* \add due to\add* the wickedness of my people, Yisrael.\x + \xo 7:12-14: \xt Josh 18:1; Psa 78:60; Jer 26:6.\x*
\v 13 \add So\add* now Yahweh declares that because you’ve all been doing those things, and I’ve spoken to you all \add over and over again\add* \add but\add* you wouldn’t listen, and I called you all \add but\add* you wouldn’t answer,
\v 14 then I’ll do what I did to Shiloh, to this house that’s called by my name—the \add temple\add* that you’ve all trusted in, and the place that I gave to you and your ancestors.
\v 15 I’ll throw you all \add away where I can’t see you\add* just as I threw out all your relatives, all of Efrayim’s descendants, \add from the northern kingdom\add*.
\s1 Yehudah’s consistent disobedience
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 16 And you, \add Yirmeyah\add*, don’t pray \add on behalf of\add* this \add group of\add* people, and don’t cry out for help, or pray for them, or petition me about them, because I won’t listen to you.
\v 17 Don’t you see what they do in Yehudah’s \add (Judah’s)\add* cities and in Yerushalem’s \add (Jerusalem’s)\add* streets?
\v 18 The sons are gathering firewood, and the fathers are kindling the fire, and the women are kneading dough to make cakes for ‘the queen of the heavens’ and pouring out drink offerings for other gods so as to provoke me to anger.\x + \xo 7:18: \xt Jer 44:17-19.\x*
\v 19 Yahweh \add declares\add* that it’s not me they’re provoking, \add but rather it’s themselves\add* \add that they’re hurting\add* \add to their own\add* shame.
\v 20 So my master Yahweh, says this: “Listen, my \add anger and rage\add* will gush out onto this place—onto people and animals, and trees in the countryside and \add crops in\add* the ground. It will burn and not be extinguished.”
\p
\v 21 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says: “Instead of \add wasting time\add* burning up your sacrifices, \add just\add* eat the meat \add yourselves\add*,
\v 22 because on the day when I brought your ancestors out from Egypt, I didn’t \add immediately\add* \add give them orders\add* about burnt offerings and sacrifices.
\v 23 \add What I told them was\add*, ‘Listen to my voice, and I’ll be your god, and you all will be my people. \add Follow all the instructions that I’ll give\add* you so that \add everything\add* will go well for you all.’
\v 24 \add But\add* they didn’t turn their \add heads\add* towards him and listen, and they \add enacted\add* schemes from the stubbornness of their own evil hearts—going backwards instead of forwards
\v 25 from the day that their ancestors left Egypt even until today. Then I sent my servants the prophets to you all—\add rising early each day\add* and sending \add them\add*.
\v 26 \add However,\add* they didn’t listen to me, and they stiffened their necks and \add turned their heads\add*—doing even more evil than their ancestors.
\p
\v 27 \add So pass\add* all these messages on to them, \add even though\add* they won’t listen to you.
\q1 You’ll call to them, \add but\add* they won’t answer you.
\v 28 Tell them that this is a nation that doesn’t listen to the voice of its god Yahweh, and doesn’t accept discipline.
\s1 ‘The Valley of Slaughter’
\q1
\v 29 Shave your \add head\add* \add in mourning\add* and throw \add the hair\add* away.
\q1 Sing a mourning song on the barren heights
\q1 because Yahweh has rejected and abandoned the generation \add who made him angry\add*.
\p
\v 30 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh says that Yehudah’s people have done \add what I consider evil\add*—putting disgusting things in the \add temple that’s associated with\add* my name, \add and so have defiled it\add*.
\v 31 They’ve built \add hilltop shrines\add* to Tofet in Hinnom Valley \add outside Yerushalem (Jerusalem)\add* to burn their sons and daughters in fire—something I’ve \add never\add* commanded \add or even considered\add*.\x + \xo 7:31: a \xt 2Ki 23:10; Jer 32:35; \xo b \xt Lev 18:21.\x*
\v 32 So listen, Yahweh says, that days are coming because of that that, when it’ll no longer be called ‘Tofet’ or ‘Hinnom Valley’, but rather, ‘The Valley of Slaughter’, because \add so many people will be buried in Tofet that they’ll run out of space\add*.
\v 33 Then the people’s corpses will become food for the \add vultures\add* and the \add wild animals\add*, and there’ll be no one \add left\add* to frighten them \add away\add*.
\v 34 Then in Yehudah’s cities and Yerushalem’s streets, I’ll halt the sounds of joy and gladness, \add even wedding celebrations\add*, because \add the region\add* will become a wasteland.\x + \xo 7:34: \xt Jer 16:9; 25:10; Rev 18:23.\x*
\c 8
\p
\v 1 Yahweh declares that they will bring the bones of Yehudah’s \add (Judah’s)\add* kings out from their graves at that time, as well as the bones of their leaders, priests, and prophets, along with the bones of Yerushalem’s \add (Jerusalem’s)\add* inhabitants.
\v 2 Then they’ll spread them out under the sun, moon, and stars—\add the heavenly bodies\add* that they loved and served, and that they \add followed\add* after and searched for, and that they bowed down to. \add Those bones\add* won’t be collected up, and they won’t be buried again. They’ll be \add like\add* dung \add across the surface\add* of the land.
\v 3 The remnant of that evil \add group of people\add* in all those places where I banished them, will choose death rather than life. That is Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Sin and punishment
\p
\v 4 Then Yahweh says to tell them:
\q1 Don’t people get back up when they fall down?
\q1 Don’t they \add come back\add* after they’ve turned \add the wrong way\add*?
\q1
\v 5 \add So\add* Why do these people from Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* turn and away, \add then continue to be unfaithful\add*?
\q1 They keep hold of deceitfulness and refuse to \add come back\add*.
\q1
\v 6 I’ve \add listened carefully but they don’t say the right things\add*.
\q1 None of them \add wants to give up\add* their wickedness.
\q1 ^All of them \add carry on\add* their own ways, like a horse rushing \add forward\add* in battle.
\q1
\v 7 Even the stork \add as it flies\add*, knows \add the seasons\add*.
\q1 The dove, swallow, and thrush \add stick to their migration times\add*,
\q1 ^\add yet\add* my people do know what Yahweh \add expects of them\add*.
\q1
\v 8 How can you all say that you’re wise and that you have Yahwehs instructions?
\q1 \add Honestly,\add* the \add quills\add* of deceitful scribes have made it into a lie.
\q1
\v 9 The wise will be put to shame—
\q1 they will be dismayed and trapped.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* they’ve rejected Yahweh’s message.
\q1 What wisdom \add do they really have\add*?
\q1
\v 10 \add Because of that,\add* I’ll give their wives to others,
\q1 and their fields to those who dispossess \add them\add*,
\q1 because they’re all \add prospering by taking advantage of others\add*—
\q1 prophets and priests are all \add behaving deceptively\add*.
\q1
\v 11 They lightly treated the fracture of my people’s daughter,
\q1 saying, ‘Peace, peace,’ when there’s no peace.\x + \xo 8:11: \xt Eze 13:10.\x*
\q1
\v 12 Were they ashamed when they did \add something disgusting\add*?
\q1 Even \add when confronted\add*, they weren’t ashamed—
\q1 they didn’t know how to be humiliated\x + \xo 8:10-12: \xt Jer 6:12-15.\x*
\q1 so they’ll fall \add like the others\add*.
\q1 They’ll stumble at the time of their \add punishment\add* says Yahweh.
\p
\v 13 I’ll bring their \add harvests\add* to an end, says Yahweh.
\q1 There won’t be any grapes on their vines, or figs on their trees.
\q1 Even the leaves will wither,
\q1 and what I gave them, will \add rot\add* away.
\p
\v 14 \add Why are we just sitting here\add*?
\q1 →Let’s go into the fortified cities \add together\add* so we can die there,
\q1 because our god Yahweh is going to cause us to perish,
\q1 and he’ll make us drink poisoned water because we’ve sinned against \add him\add*.
\q1
\v 15 We had hoped for peace, \add but nothing\add* good \add came\add*.
\q1 \add We hoped\add* for a time of healing, \add but wow,\add* \add got\add* terror.
\q1
\v 16 The snorting of his stallions could be heard from Dan.
\q1 The whole earth shakes from the sound of the neighing of his powerful \add horses\add*.
\q1 They are coming to \add destroy\add* the land and everything in it,
\q1 \add and\add* the city and \add everyone living in it\add*.
\p
\v 17 \add Yes, listen,\add* I’ll send snakes\f + \fr 8:17 \ft This could likely be referring to enemy warriors, not literal snakes.\f* among you all—
\q1 vipers \add that can’t be charmed\add*,
\q1 →and they’ll bite you all, says Yahweh.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s sorrow about Yehudah
\s4 Southern kingdom
\q1
\v 18 My sorrow is \add beyond comfort\add*.
\q1 My heart is faint within me.
\q1
\v 19 Listen, it’s the sound of a cry for help from my people’s daughter from a far away land.
\q1 Isn’t Yahweh in Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*?
\q1 Is its king no longer there?
\q1 Why have they provoked me to anger with their idols and with useless foreign \add gods\add*?
\q1
\v 20 The harvest has passed, summer has ended,
\q1 and we haven’t been rescued.
\b
\q1
\v 21 I’m broken because of the brokenness of my people’s daughter.
\q1 I’m in mourning \add and\add* \add overwhelmed by depression\add*.
\q1
\v 22 Is there no medicine in Gilead?
\q1 Isn’t there a doctor there?
\q1 Why isn’t my people’s daughter \add getting healed\add*?
\c 9
\q1
\v 1 If only my head was water, and my eyes were a fountain of tears,
\q1 →then I’d weep day and night for my people’s slain daughter.
\q1
\v 2 Who will give me a lodging place for travellers in the desert?
\q1 Then I would leave my people and walk away from them,
\q1 because all of them are adulterers—
\q1 a treacherous group of people.
\q1
\v 3 They bend their tongues \add like\add* bows—
\q1 \add chasing\add* lies rather than faithfulness.
\q1 They grow strong in the land
\q1 because they go from evil to evil and they don’t know me.
\m That’s Yahweh’s declaration.
\b
\q1
\v 4 Let each \add person\add* \add beware of\add* his neighbour,
\q1 and don’t rely on any \add relative\add*,
\q1 because brothers consistently betray,
\q1 and neighbours go around slandering.
\q1
\v 5 Every one will deceive their neighbour,
\q1 and they won’t tell the truth—
\q1 they teach their tongues to tell lies.
\q1 →They \add wear themselves out being disobedient\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Your residence is in the middle of deceit—
\q1 \add because of\add* deceit they refuse to know me.
\m That’s Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 7 \add Because of that\add*, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says,
\q1 I’m about to refine them and test them,
\q1 because how \add else\add* should I act \add towards\add* my people’s daughter.
\q1
\v 8 Their tongue is a \add deadly\add* arrow—
\q1 it speaks out deceit.
\q1 With his mouth, \add a man\add* speaks peace with his neighbours,
\q1 while in his \add mind\add*, he’s \add planning\add* his ambush.
\q1
\v 9 Shouldn’t I \add punish\add* them for those things? Yahweh says.
\q1 Shouldn’t I avenge myself against a nation like that?
\b
\q1
\v 10 On the mountains I’ll take up weeping and wailing,
\q1 and a funeral song out in the wilderness pastures,
\q1 because they’re left desolate as no one passes through \add there\add*.
\q1 They don’t hear the sound of cattle or birds or \add wild\add* animals—
\q1 they’ve fled \add and\add* gone away.
\b
\q1
\v 11 Then I’ll make Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* into piles of ruins—
\q1 a place for jackals to live in—
\q1 and I’ll make Yehudah’s \add (Judah’s)\add* cities into uninhabited wastelands.
\p
\v 12 Who is the \add person\add* that’s wise and understands this?
\q1 Who has Yahweh’s mouth spoken to so that they can declare it—
\q1 concerning why the \add nation\add* has perished and been destroyed
\q1 like the wilderness with no one passing through \add it\add*?
\p
\v 13 Then Yahweh said, “Because they abandoned my instructions that I \add gave to\add* them,
\q1 and they don’t listen to my voice \add or follow what say\add*,
\q1
\v 14 and they’re \add guided\add* by their own \add stubborn minds\add*,
\q1 and follow after the Baal that their ancestors taught them about,
\q1
\v 15 then Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, I’m about to feed them \add bitter food\add*
\q1 and give them poison water to drink.
\q1
\v 16 Then I’ll scatter them among nations that neither they nor their ancestors \add knew anything about\add*,
\q1 and I’ll send \add an army\add* after them until I’ve \add finished them off\add*.
\s1 The requesting of people of Yerushalem
\p
\v 17 Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 Consider \add that\add* and summon funeral wailers to come—
\q1 get the most skillful \add women\add* to come.
\p
\v 18 Let them hurry and \add start wailing about\add* us,
\q1 →so our eyes have tears running down them,
\q1 and our eyelids flow with water,
\p
\v 19 because the sound of mourning can be heard from Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*:
\q1 ‘We’ve been \add so\add* devastated.
\q1 We’re terribly ashamed, because we’ve left the land
\q1 because they tore down our \add houses\add*.’
\p
\v 20 \add So now\add* hear Yahweh’s message, \add you\add* women.
\q1 Let your ear receive the message from his mouth,
\q1 and teach your daughters a mourning song,
\q1 and each woman \add teach\add* her neighbour a funeral song,
\q1
\v 21 because death has come up into our windows.
\q1 It enters into our fortresses,
\q1 cutting off children from the street
\q1 and young men from the open \add plazas\add*.
\q1
\v 22 Yahweh says to \add pass this on\add*:
\q1 Human corpses will fall like dung \add across the ground’s surface\add*
\q1 and like fallen grain after the harvesters \add have finished\add*,
\q1 and there’s no one to collect \add them\add*.
\p
\v 23 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Don’t let the wise \add person\add* boast about their wisdom,
\q1 and don’t let the warrior boast about his strength.
\q1 Don’t let the rich \add person\add* boast about their riches,
\q1
\v 24 because if \add they\add* want to boast, let them boast about this:
\q1 Understanding and knowing me because I’m Yahweh,
\q1 \add demonstrating\add* loyal commitment, justice, and righteousness on the earth
\q1 because I take pleasure in those \add things\add*.\x + \xo 9:24: \xt 1Cor 1:31; 2Cor 10:17.\x*
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 25 Listen, Yahweh declares that \add there’s a time\add* coming
\q1 \add when\add* I will \add punish\add* all \add those who’ve been physically\add* circumcised:
\q1
\v 26 the Egyptians, Judeans, Edomites, Ammonites, and Moabites,
\q1 and all those who \add trim the corners\add* \add of their beards\add*, those living in the wilderness,
\q1 because all the uncircumcised nations and all the \add Israelis\add* have uncircumcised hearts.
\c 10
\s1 Idolatry versus true worship
\p
\v 1 Listen to the message that Yahweh is telling you all, \add you\add* \add Israelis\add*.
\v 2 This is what Yahweh says:
\q1 Don’t \add imitate\add* the ways of \add other\add* nations,
\q1 and don’t be dismayed by signs in the skies,
\q1 \add just\add* because \add those other\add* nations \add are\add*,
\q1
\v 3 because the customs of \add those groups of\add* people are worthless.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* they cut down a tree from a forest,
\q1 \add and\add* a craftsman does his handywork with his tools,
\q1
\v 4 then they \add overlay\add* it with gold and silver.
\q1 They \add use hammer and nails to securely fasten it\add*
\q1 \add so that\add* it won’t \add topple over\add*.
\q1
\v 5 \add Those idols\add* are like a scarecrow in a cucumber field,
\q1 \add not being able to\add* speak.
\q1 \add What’s more,\add* they have to be carried because they can’t walk.
\q1 Don’t be afraid of them because they can’t harm \add anyone\add*,
\q1 \add but at the same time,\add* there’s no good in them \add either\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 There’s no one like you, Yahweh.
\q1 You’re powerful and \add have a reputation for your\add* strength.
\q1
\v 7 Who wouldn’t \add respect and obey\add* you, king of the nations
\q1 because \add that’s what you deserve\add*?\x + \xo 10:7: \xt Rev 15:4.\x*
\q1 \add Yes,\add* among all the wise \add people\add* of the \add word\add*,
\q1 and among all their kingdoms,
\q1 there’s no one like you.
\q1
\v 8 \add Those ‘wise’ people\add* are \add both\add* stupid and foolish \add all at once\add*—
\q1 instructed by an idol that’s \add just a piece of\add* wood.
\q1
\v 9 They brought hammered silver from Tarshish and gold from Ufaz—
\q1 the work of a craftsman and from the hands of the refiners.
\q1 \add Then they put\add* violet and purple clothing \add on them\add*—
\q1 all the work of skillful people.
\q1
\v 10 \add However,\add* Yahweh is the true god.
\q1 He is the living god and permanent king.
\q1 \add When\add* he’s angry, the earth shakes,
\q1 and the nations can’t endure his indignation.
\p
\v 11 You \add need to tell\add* them this:
\q1 The gods that didn’t make the heavens and earth
\q1 will perish from the earth and from under these skies.
\s1 Praising Yahweh
\q1
\v 12 \add Yahweh\add* made the earth using his power.
\q1 He established the world by his wisdom,
\q1 and with his understanding, he stretched out the skies.
\q1
\v 13 \add When he projects\add* his voice, there’s a rush of waters in the skies,
\q1 and he brings clouds up from the \add ends\add* of the earth.
\q1 He made lightning for the rain,
\q1 and sends out wind from his storehouse.
\q1
\v 14 Every person has become stupid from knowledge.
\q1 Every metalworker is put to shame by \add idols\add*
\q1 because his molten image is a deception and there’s no \add life\add* in them.
\q1
\v 15 They’re worthless—a work of mockery.
\q1 They’ll perish at the time for their punishment.
\q1
\v 16 Yakov’s \add (Jacob’s)\add* inheritance isn’t like that
\q1 because he’s the one who made everything,
\q1 and the \add Israelis\add* are his inheritance.
\q1 His name is Commander-in-chief Yahweh.
\s1 Coming destruction for Yehudah
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 17 Gather your \add stuff\add* and leave the land,
\q1 you who are living under siege
\q1
\v 18 because Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, I’m flinging out the inhabitants of the land at this time,
\q1 and I’ll cause them distress so that they can find \add me\add*.
\p
\v 19 \add Oh dear, poor\add* me. My fracture, my wound is severe,
\q1 \add but\add* I said that this is a sickness and I will endure it.
\q1
\v 20 My tent has been devastated, and all of my tent ropes have been snapped.
\q1 My sons have gone off and left me.
\q1 There’s no one to pitch my tent again,
\q1 or to hang up my tent curtains.
\b
\q1
\v 21 \add Yes,\add* the shepherds are stupid and \add haven’t asked Yahweh for direction\add*
\q1 so therefore they haven’t prospered, and all their flock has been scattered.
\q1
\v 22 Listen, \add it sounds like news has arrived\add*
\q1 plus there’s a loud rumble from a land in the north
\q1 coming to make Yehudah’s \add (Judah’s)\add* cities into deserted places for jackals to live in.
\b
\q1
\v 23 Yahweh, I know that a person’s \add life\add* pathway isn’t their own—
\q1 no one who walks, directs their own steps.
\q1
\v 24 Discipline me, Yahweh, only in justice and not in anger
\q1 in case you reduce me to nothing.
\q1
\v 25 Pour your fury out on the nations that don’t know you.
\q1 and on the families that don’t call \add out to you to help them\add*,
\q1 because they’ve consumed Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* they’ve \add completely destroyed\add* him and \add ruined his farmland\add*.
\c 11
\s1 The broken agreement
\s4 Both kingdoms
\p
\v 1 Yahweh’s message came to Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add* to say:
\v 2 Listen to the words of this agreement and tell them to everyone in Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*, \add including those who live in\add* Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*
\v 3 and tell them, “Yisrael’s god Yahweh says that anyone who won’t listen to the words of this agreement will be cursed.
\v 4 \add It’s the same agreement\add* that I commanded for your ancestors \add at the time\add* when I brought them out of the iron furnace \add that was\add* Egypt, telling them: ‘Listen to my voice and \add follow the instructions that I’ve given\add* you all, and then you’ll be \add my\add* people, and I’ll become your god
\v 5 in order to \add fulfill\add* the promise that I made to your ancestors to give them a land that’s flowing with milk and honey, as it is \add right now\add*.’ ”
\p “So be it, Yahweh,” I answered.
\p
\v 6 Then Yahweh told me, “Proclaim all these things in Yehudah’s cities, including in Yerushalem’s streets. Tell them to listen to the words of this agreement and carry them out
\v 7 because I solemnly warned your ancestors \add at the time when\add* I brought them out of Egypt until \add today\add*, \add repeatedly\add* warning \add them\add* to listen to my voice.
\v 8 \add However,\add* they didn’t listen \add or even pay any attention to me\add*, and each one of them \add stubbornly followed their own evil desires\add*, \add so\add* I ordered all the \add consequences from not obeying\add* the agreement, to come to them.”
\p
\v 9 Then Yahweh told me, “A conspiracy has been found \add across\add* Yehudah, and including Yerushalem’s inhabitants.
\v 10 They’ve returned to the \add evil ways\add* of their ancestors \add from the past\add* who refused to listen to my messages, and then they \add followed\add* after other gods to serve them. The people of \add both\add* Yisrael and Yehudah broke the agreement that I made with the ancestors.
\v 11 \add So now,\add*, listen: Yahweh says that I’m about to bring calamity to them which they won’t be able to \add avoid\add*, and they’ll cry out to me \add for help\add* \add but\add* I won’t listen to them.
\v 12 Then Yehudah’s cities, including those living in Yerushalem, will go and cry out to the gods for help that they’ve been \add burning incense to\add*, but \add those gods\add* won’t be able to rescue them \add from\add* their calamity
\v 13 because \add there are now as many gods in Yehudah as you all have cities, and as many incense altars for Baal in Yerushalem as you all have\add* streets.
\v 14 \add Yirmeyah\add*, don’t pray for those people, and don’t \add plead with me to rescue them\add*, because I won’t be listening \add when\add* they call out to me \add for help\add* during their \add difficulties\add*.
\p
\v 15 “My dear \add Yehudah\add*, what \add right do you have\add* to be in my \add temple\add* after doing so much evil?
\q1 You \add offer holy sacrifices then go and happily do wicked things\add*.
\q1
\v 16 Yahweh called you a luxuriant olive tree with beautiful, \add good-looking\add* fruit.
\q1 ^\add Now\add* he’ll kindle a fire with a loud roar on its branches that \add have gone\add* bad.
\p
\v 17 Commander-in-chief Yahweh who planted you, has \add decided that you’ll experience evil\add* because of the evil done by the \add peoples\add* of Yisrael and Yehudah when they’ve provoked me to anger by \add offering incense\add* to Baal.
\s1 A plot against Yirmeyah
\p
\v 18 Then Yahweh revealed \add something\add* to me \add which\add* I \add understood once he\add* showed me their \add preparations\add*.
\v 19 I was like a tame lamb being led to be slaughtered, and I didn’t know that they had \add made\add* plans against me, \add saying,\add* ‘Let’s destroy the tree with its fruit, and cut him off from the land of the living. Then his name won’t be remembered any longer.’
\p
\v 20 \add Then I prayed,\add* “Commander-in-chief Yahweh who \add always\add* judges \add fairly\add*, examining \add our inner thoughts and motives\add*, let me see your vengeance on them, because I’ve \add presented\add* my case to you.”
\p
\v 21 So Yahweh said it was \add some\add* men of Anatot\f + \fr 11:21 \ft Yirmeyah’s home town—see 1:1.\f* who were \add wanting to kill me\add*, saying that I mustn’t prophesy in Yahweh’s name \add or else they’d make sure that I die\add*.
\v 22 Therefore Commander-in-chief Yahweh says, “Listen, I’m about to \add punish\add* them. \add Their\add* young men will die by the sword, and their \add children\add* will die from famine.
\v 23 There won’t \add be any of them left\add*, because I will bring calamity to the people from Anatot \add at the time\add* of their punishment.”
\c 12
\s1 Yirmeyah queries Yahweh
\q1
\v 1 Yahweh, you \add do what’s right\add* when I bring you a case.
\q1 →Nevertheless, I \add want to\add* talk with you about \add justice\add*:
\q1 Why do wicked \add people\add* prosper?
\q1 Why are treacherous people \add able to relax\add*?
\q1
\v 2 You planted them \add like trees\add* and they’ve taken root,
\q1 \add then\add* they’ve grown and produced fruit.
\q1 \add They’re full of talk about\add* you,
\q1 \add but they’re really far from you\add*.
\q1
\v 3 \add but\add* Yahweh, you know me.
\q1 You see me, and test my heart toward you.
\q1 Drag them away like sheep \add doing\add* to slaughter,
\q1 and \add reserve a time for them to be slaughtered\add*.
\q1
\v 4 \add How much longer will the land be dry for\add*
\q1 with the plants in the countryside withering up?
\q1 Even the wild animals and birds have \add diminished in number\add*,
\q1 because people have said that he won’t see \add what will happen to us\add*.
\s2 Yahweh’s response to Yirmeyah
\p
\v 5 If you’ve run with foot soldiers and they’ve \add worn you out\add*,
\q1 how will you compete with horses?
\q1 \add If\add* you’re falling to the ground in a safe \add region\add*,
\q1 how will you do in the thickets by the Yarden \add (Jordan) river\add*?
\q1
\v 6 Even your brothers and \add other family members\add* \add are working against\add* you.
\q1 They \add speak out against\add* you.
\q1 Don’t trust them \add when\add* they say good things \add about you\add*.
\s1 Yahweh’s distress about his people
\p
\v 7 I’ve abandoned my \add country\add*.
\q1 I’ve \add walked away from\add* my inheritance.
\q1 I’ve given my dearly loved \add one\add* into the \add hand\add* of its enemies.
\q1
\v 8 My inheritance become like a lion in a forest for me.
\q1 \add That country\add* \add always speaks against me\add* so I hate it.
\q1
\v 9 My inheritance is like a speckled bird of prey to me,
\q1 with \add other\add* birds of prey all around it.
\q1 Go \add and\add* get all the wild animals from the countryside \add to come and eat\add*.
\q1
\v 10 Many shepherds \add (foreign rulers)\add* have ruined my vineyard—
\q1 they’ve trampled my \add area\add*.
\q1 They’ve made my desirable \add region\add* into a desolate wasteland.
\q1
\v 11 \add They’ve\add* made it into a wasteland—it’s mourning to me.
\q1 All the land has been made desolate because there’s no one \add who cares about it\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Destroyers have come to all the bare hilltops in the wilderness,
\q1 because a sword is devouring for Yahweh, from each end of the land.
\q1 There’s no peace for \add any living thing\add*.
\q1
\v 13 People have sown wheat and harvested thorns.
\q1 They’ve wearied themselves but not profited,
\q1 and \add they\add* were ashamed by your \add low production\add*
\q1 \add resulting\add* from Yahweh’s \add fierce\add* anger.
\s1 The what was said of God concerning the nations surrounding Yisrael
\p
\v 14 Yahweh says this: All my evil neighbours who touch the inheritance that I gave to my \add Israeli\add* people, listen, I’ll uproot them from the land, and I’ll uproot Yehudah’s descendants from among them.
\v 15 Then after I’ve uprooted them, I’ll have compassion on them \add again\add*, and I’ll bring them back—each \add one\add* back to their own inheritance and their own land.
\v 16 If they’ll properly learn the ways of my people, to \add make promises using\add* my name saying, ‘As Yahweh lives,’ instead of how my people were taught to \add make promises\add* by Baal, then they’ll \add prosper and be my people\add* \add again\add*.
\v 17 \add However\add* if they won’t listen \add when\add* I uproot the nation, then I’ll uproot it \add to\add* destroy it. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\c 13
\s1 Yirmeyah buries a loincloth
\p
\v 1 Yahweh told me this: Go and buy yourself a linen loincloth and put it on, \add but don’t let it get near\add* water.
\v 2 \add So\add* I bought a loincloth as Yahweh had told me to, and I put it on.
\v 3 Then Yahweh \add gave\add* me a second \add instruction\add*, saying:
\v 4 Take the loincloth that you bought and you’re wearing, and \add pack up\add* and go to Perat\f + \fr 13:4 \ft About 6km away from Anatot. It’s possible that the Euphrates River is being referred to here, although less likely as that was a trip of over a thousand kilometres.\f* and \add bury\add* it in a crack in the rock.
\v 5 \add So\add* I went and hid it at Perat just as Yahweh had told me to.
\p
\v 6 Then after many days, Yahweh told me to \add get ready\add* and go to Perat \add to retrieve\add* the loincloth that \add he’d told me\add* to \add bury\add* there.
\v 7 \add So\add* I went to Perat and dug the loincloth out from the crack that I’d hidden it in, \add but wow,\add* \add it\add* was ruined and \add totally worthless\add*.
\p
\v 8 Then Yahweh \add gave\add* me this message:
\v 9 Yahweh says that I’ll \add rot away\add* the pride of Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*, including the pride of the great Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*.
\v 10 That wicked \add nation\add* that refused to listen to my messages, who are \add following their own stubborn desires\add* and have \add followed\add* other god by serving them and bowing down to them, let \add that nation\add* become like that loincloth that’s \add no good\add* for anything.
\v 11 Yahweh declares that just like a loincloth \add is hitched\add* to someone’s hips, so too I’ve made all \add those from\add* Yisrael and Yehudah cling to me, to be my people who would \add bring me fame\add*, praise, and honour, \add but\add* they didn’t listen.
\s1 Filled with wine
\p
\v 12 \add So\add* you must \add pass this message along\add* to them: Yisrael’s god Yahweh says that every jar will be filled with wine, and they’ll tell you, ‘Of course we know that every jar will be filled with wine.’
\v 13 \add So\add* tell them that Yahweh says this: Listen, I’m about to fill all the inhabitants of this land with drunkenness—the kings that sit of David’s throne, the priests and prophets, and all of Yerushalem’s inhabitants.
\v 14 Then Yahweh declares: I’ll \add cause a drunken brawl among\add* brothers, parents, and children. I won’t pity you or have compassion, and I won’t spare them from \add destruction\add*.
\s1 Yirmeyah warns against pride
\s4 Southern kingdom
\q1
\v 15 Listen and \add pay attention\add*.
\q1 Don’t be arrogant, because Yahweh has spoken.
\q1
\v 16 Give \add honour\add* to your god Yahweh before he brings darkness,
\q1 and before he causes \add you all\add* to stumble on the mountains at twilight,
\q1 because you’re hoping for light, but he’ll \add turn the place\add* into deep darkness—into a dark cloud.
\q1
\v 17 \add But\add* if you all won’t listen,
\q1 I’ll weep \add in private\add* because of your arrogance.
\q1 Tears will run down my eyes because Yahweh’s flock has been taken captive.
\p
\v 18 Tell the king and the queen mother to take a low seat
\q1 because their splendid crowns have \add been removed\add* \add from their heads\add*.
\q1
\v 19 The cities of the Negev have been shut up,
\q1 and there’s no one to open them \add again\add*.
\q1 Yehudah has been taken into exile—
\q1 they’ve all been taken far away.
\p
\v 20 \add Look up\add* and see them coming from the north.
\q1 Where’s the flock that was given to you—\add those beautiful\add* sheep?
\q1
\v 21 What will you say when the allies that you taught, he sets over you?
\q1 Won’t labour pains \add hit\add* you like a woman giving birth?
\q1
\v 22 Then \add as a country\add* you’ll \add ask\add* why those things have happened to you.
\q1 It’s the \add magnitude of your disobedience\add* that’s caused your skirt to be lifted
\q1 and your \add body\add* to be \add treated with\add* violence.
\q1
\v 23 An Ethiopian \add person\add* can’t change their skin \add colour\add*
\q1 and a leopard can’t change its spots.
\q1 \add Similarly\add* you all aren’t able to do good
\q1 as you’re all so accustomed to doing evil.
\q1
\v 24 I’ll scatter them like \add straw\add* that’s \add blown across\add* the wilderness by the wind.
\q1
\v 25 Yahweh declares that that’s your part of your inheritance
\q1 as you’ve forgotten me and trusted in \add lies\add*.
\q1
\v 26 \add So\add* I’ll also pull your \add skirt\add* up over your face
\q1 and then your shame will become visible.
\q1
\v 27 I’ve seen your adultery and neighing—
\q1 the wickedness of your prostitution on the hills and across the countryside.
\q1 I’ve seen your detestable \add behaviour\add*.
\q1 \add You won’t end well\add*, Yerushalem.
\q1 How long will you remain ‘unclean’?
\c 14
\s1 The terrible drought
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 1 This is Yahweh’s message to Yirmeyah regarding droughts:
\q1
\v 2 Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* is in mourning and its gates are neglected.
\q1 They’re mourning for the land
\q1 and Yerushalem is crying out \add in distress\add*.
\q1
\v 3 The \add leading citizens\add* send their servants out for water,
\q1 \add but\add* when they get to the wells, they didn’t find any.
\q1 They return \add with empty containers\add*—
\q1 ashamed and humiliated, and with their heads covered \add in grief\add*.
\q1
\v 4 The ground is cracked open because \add there hasn’t been any\add* rain.
\q1 The farmers are ashamed—they’ve covered their heads \add in grief\add*,
\q1
\v 5 because even the doe in the countryside \add abandoned her newborn fawn\add* as there was no grass.
\q1
\v 6 Wild donkeys stand on bare hills and pant for breath like jackals—
\q1 their eyes have failed because there’s no vegetation.
\q1
\v 7 Even though our transgressions testify against us,
\q1 \add do something\add*, Yahweh, for the sake of your \add reputation\add*
\q1 because we sinned against you with our \add frequent rebellion\add*.
\q1
\v 8 \add You\add* are Yisrael’s hope—the one who \add rescues\add* it at a time of distress.
\q1 Why would you \add act\add* like a stranger in the land—
\q1 like a traveller who’s \add stopped in to stay\add* the night.
\q1
\v 9 \add Why are you like someone just standing there with their mouth open\add*—
\q1 like a warrior who’s \add powerless\add* to save \add someone\add*?
\q1 You’re \add here\add* among us, Yahweh, and \add we’ve been calling out to you\add* \add to rescue us\add*.
\q1 Don’t abandon us.
\p
\v 10 This is what Yahweh says about this \add nation\add*:
\q1 They love to wander, so they’ve \add gone wherever their feet take them\add*,
\q1 →\add but\add* Yahweh hasn’t accepted them.
\q1 Now he’ll remember their \add wickedness\add*
\q1 and he’ll punish them for their \add disobedience\add*.
\p
\v 11 Yahweh told me, “Don’t pray for good \add to come to\add* this \add nation\add*
\v 12 because \add even\add* if they fast, I won’t listen to their petition, and when they offer up a burnt offering and a grain offering, I won’t be accepting them, because I’m bringing an end to them by the sword, and famine, and disease.”
\p
\v 13 Then I said, “Oh no, my master Yahweh. Listen, the prophets are telling \add the people\add* that \add they\add* won’t \add experience war or\add* famine because \add you’ll\add* give \add them\add* \add ongoing\add* peace in this place.”
\p
\v 14 “The prophets \add use my name but speak deceitfully\add*,” Yahweh \add answered\add*. “I didn’t appoint them and I didn’t send them, and I didn’t \add give\add* them a false vision. The \add worthless prophecies that they’re proclaiming\add* to you all \add come\add* from their own \add minds\add*.”
\v 15 Therefore Yahweh says, “\add Now\add* those prophets who I never sent \add but\add* who are \add using\add* my name and say that no \add war or\add* famine will happen in this \add region\add*, \add well\add* those prophets will meet their \add own\add* ends through \add war\add* and famine.
\v 16 Then the people that they prophesied to will be thrown out into Yerushalem’s streets because of famine and \add war\add*. No one will be there to bury them or their wives, sons, or daughters, \add as\add* I’ll pour their wickedness out onto them.
\p
\v 17 Then you’ll \add pass\add* this message onto them:
\q1 Day and night the tears run down my eyes.
\q1 Don’t let them stop, because of the terrible \add damage\add*
\q1 as my virgin daughter has been \add shattered\add*—
\q1 my people have \add received\add* a very severe wound.
\q1
\v 18 If I go out into the countryside, wow, I see those who were killed by the sword.
\q1 Then if I go into the city, wow, there’s diseases \add caused by\add* famine,
\q1 because both prophets and priests \add have gone into a land that they weren’t familiar with\add*.
\s1 Pleading for mercy
\s4 Southern kingdom
\q1
\v 19 Have you completely rejected Yehudah \add (Judah)\add*?
\q1 Do you really hate Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*?
\q1 Why have you struck us \add when\add* there’s no healing for us?
\q1 We eagerly hoped for peace, but there was nothing good.
\q1 \add We hoped\add* for a time of healing, but wow, \add we got\add* terror!
\q1
\v 20 Yahweh, we acknowledge our wickedness—
\q1 the transgression of our ancestors.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* we’ve sinned against you.
\q1
\v 21 For the sake of your \add reputation\add*, don’t reject \add us\add*.
\q1 Don’t treat \add the place hosting\add* your \add wonderful\add* throne with contempt.
\q1 Remember your agreement with us, and don’t break it.
\q1
\v 22 Do those useless \add idols\add* from other countries send rain?
\q1 Do they cause showers \add to fall\add*?
\q1 Isn’t it you, our god Yahweh, \add who does that\add*?
\q1 We eagerly wait for you, because \add you’re the one\add* who does all those \add things\add*.
\c 15
\s1 Yehudah’s coming destruction
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh told me, “Even if Mosheh \add (Moses)\add* or Shemuel \add (Samuel)\add* were standing in front of me, I still wouldn’t be in favour of this \add group of\add* people. Send them out away from me, and let them go away.\x + \xo 15:1: a \xt Exo 32:11-14; Num 14:13-19; \xo b \xt 1Sam 7:5-9.\x*
\v 2 If \add anyone comes to ask\add* you where \add they\add* should go, tell them that this is what Yahweh says:
\q1 Those who are \add destined\add* for death, \add will die\add*.
\q1 Those for the sword, \add will die in war\add*.
\q1 Those for famine, \add will suffer starvation\add*.
\q1 Those for exile, \add will be taken away in captivity\add*.\x + \xo 15:2: \xt Rev 13:10.\x*
\p
\v 3 Yahweh declares that \add he’ll\add* assign them to four groups:
\li1 1. killed by the sword,
\li1 2. dragged away by \add wild\add* dogs,
\li1 3. \add assigned\add* to the birds \add of prey\add*, and
\li1 4. \add assigned\add* to be devoured and destroyed by \add wild\add* animals.
\m
\v 4 Because of what Yehudah’s King Menashsheh \add (Manasseh)\add* did in Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*, I’ll make people in all the world’s nations be horrified by them.\x + \xo 15:4: \xt 2Ki 21:1-16; 2Ch 33:1-9.\x*
\p
\v 5 \add Yes,\add* who will \add feel sorry\add* for you, Yerushalem,
\q1 and who will show sympathy for you?
\q1 Who will \add go out of their way\add* to ask about your welfare?
\q1
\v 6 Yahweh declares: You’ve forsaken me—
\q1 you’ve turned your back on me
\q1 \add so\add* I’ve \add used my power against\add* you \add to\add* destroy you.
\q1 I’m tired of \add letting you off\add*.
\q1
\v 7 \add So\add* I’ll winnow them with a pitchfork at the \add country’s\add* gates.
\q1 I’ll make them childless, \add thus\add* destroying my people
\q1 as they haven’t turned from their \add own\add* ways.
\q1
\v 8 I’ll make more widows for them than sand \add grains\add* on the \add beach\add*.
\q1 I’ll send a destroyer against the \add mothers\add* of their young \add men\add* at midday.
\q1 I’ll make shock and horror fall on them suddenly.
\q1
\v 9 The mother who has borne seven children will waste away.
\q1 She’ll gasp—her sun will set while it is still daytime.
\q1 She’ll be ashamed and embarrassed, because I will give those who remain
\q1 to \add be killed by\add* the sword in their enemies’ presence.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s complaint to Yahweh
\p
\v 10 \add Poor\add* me, mother, that you gave birth to me—
\q1 a man of strife and contention throughout the \add entire region\add*.
\q1 I haven’t lent \add money\add* \add or borrowed it\add*
\q1 \add yet\add* they all curse me.
\p
\v 11 Yahweh said,
\q1 Won’t I rescue you for good?
\q1 Won’t I make your \add enemies\add* plead with you
\q1 in a time of evil and distress?
\q1
\v 12 Can \add anyone\add* break iron—
\q1 iron from the north, \add or\add* bronze?
\p
\v 13 I’ll give your wealth and treasures to your enemies as plunder \add without them having to pay\add*
\q1 as \add the price for\add* all your sins committed across all your territories.
\q1
\v 14 Then I’ll make \add you serve\add* your enemies in a land that you \add hadn’t been to before\add*
\q1 because the fire of my anger towards you all has been kindled \add and\add* will burn.
\p
\v 15 Yahweh, you know \add my situation\add*.
\q1 \add Take note of my situation\add* and bring your vengeance to those harassing me.
\q1 \add Don’t be patient with them and let them\add* take me away.
\q1 Know that \add I suffer reproach for your sake\add*.
\q1
\v 16 Your messages were found and I \add consumed\add* them.
\q1 Your message to me \add made me happy\add* and \add gave me cause for celebration\add*
\q1 because \add I bear\add* your name, Commander-in-chief Yahweh, god of armies.
\q1
\v 17 I didn’t sit among the gathering of the merry makers,
\q1 \add but rather,\add* I enjoyed \add feeling your presence\add*.
\q1 I sat alone because you’d filled me with indignation.
\q1
\v 18 Why is my pain ongoing and my wound incurable, refusing to be healed?
\q1 Will you be like a \add spring that lets me down when its supply\add* is unreliable?
\p
\v 19 So Yahweh said this:
\q1 If you return \add to me\add*, then I’ll restore you and you’ll stand in front of me
\q1 because if you \add separate out\add* the foolish \add things\add* from the precious \add things\add*,
\q1 you will be like my mouth. The people will come back to you,
\q1 \add but\add* you yourself mustn’t go back to them.
\q1
\v 20 I’ll make you like an \add impenetrable\add* bronze wall to this people,
\q1 and they’ll fight against you.
\q1 \add However,\add* they won’t defeat you,
\q1 because I’ll be with you to save you, and to rescue you.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 21 Then I’ll rescue you from the \add plots\add* of wicked \add people\add*
\q1 and I’ll \add buy your freedom\add* from the ruthless \add people\add*.
\c 16
\s1 Yirmeyah advised not to marry
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh \add gave\add* me a message, telling me:
\v 2 Don’t \add get married\add* and don’t \add have children\add* in this place
\v 3 because Yahweh says this to the \add children\add* born in this place and to the \add parents who brought them into this world\add*:
\q1
\v 4 They’ll die from disease and not be mourned \add or\add* buried—
\q1 they’ll be like dung on the ground.
\q1 They’ll come to \add their\add* \add ends\add* through \add war\add* and famine,
\q1 and their corpses will become food for the birds and the \add wild\add* animals.
\p
\v 5 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh says this:
\q1 Don’t enter a \add home where there’s a funeral\add*.
\q1 Don’t go to mourn or to show sympathy to them,
\q1 because I’ve withdrawn my peace from this people,
\q1 \add as well as my\add* compassion and loyal commitment.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 6 \add Both the important people and the ordinary people\add* will die in this land.
\q1 They won’t be buried and no one will mourn for them,
\q1 or cut themselves or shave off their hair \add to show grief\add* for them.
\q1
\v 7 No one must share any food to comfort those in mourning because of the deaths,
\q1 and no one must give a comforting cup to his father or mother.
\q1
\v 8 Don’t go to a \add dining establishment\add* to sit with them to eat and drink
\q1
\v 9 because Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, \add right\add* in front of your eyes, in your lifetime and in this place,
\q1 I’m about to make the sounds of happiness and gladness cease—
\q1 \add including\add* the sounds of \add brides and grooms\add*.\x + \xo 16:9: \xt Jer 7:34; 25:10; Rev 18:23.\x*
\p
\v 10 Then when you \add pass on\add* all these messages to the people, they’ll \add ask\add* you:
\q1 Why has Yahweh decreed all this terrible calamity against us,
\q1 and what \add wickedness or sin have we committed\add* against our god Yahweh?
\p
\v 11 \add So give\add* them this declaration from Yahweh:
\q1 It’s because your ancestors \add followed\add* after foreign gods and served them and bowed down to them.
\q1 They abandoned me and didn’t \add follow my instructions\add*.
\q1
\v 12 Then you yourselves have done \add even\add* more wickedness than your ancestors,
\q1 and everyone of you is walking by the stubbornness of their wicked heart—
\q1 not listening to me.
\q1
\v 13 \add So\add* I will throw you all out of this land,
\q1 to a land that neither you or your ancestors have \add been to\add*.
\s1 Return from exile
\p
\v 14 \add Now listen,\add* Yahweh declares:
\q1 Because of that the days are coming when \add they’ll\add* no longer say,
\q1 ‘As Yahweh, the one who brought the \add Israelis\add* out of Egypt, lives.’
\q1
\v 15 \add Instead\add* \add they’ll say\add*:
\q1 ‘As Yahweh lives, the one who brought the \add Israelis back\add* from the land of the north
\q1 and from the lands where he had driven them,’
\q1 because I’ll bring them back to the land that I gave to their ancestors.
\s1 The coming punishment
\p
\v 16 Listen, Yahweh declares:
\q1 I’ll send for many fishermen to fish \add the people\add* out.
\q1 After that, I’ll send for many hunters
\q1 to hunt them from under every mountain and hill, and from the crevices in the rocks
\q1
\v 17 because \add I’m watching everything they do\add*
\q1 and their \add wicked behaviour\add* can’t be hidden from me.
\q1
\v 18 Firstly, I’ll pay back double for their disobedience and wickedness,
\q1 because of their polluting my land with their detestable \add carvings\add*,
\q1 and because they filled my inheritance with their disgusting \add idols\add*.”
\s1 Yirmeyah thanks for safety
\p
\v 19 Yahweh, you’re my stronghold and my refuge—
\q1 my place of safety in \add any distressing time\add*.
\q1 The nations will go to you from the ends of the earth and say,
\q1 “Surely our ancestors inherited lies—
\q1 \add Those idols\add* are \add a waste of time\add* and there’s no profit in them.
\q1
\v 20 Can people make their own gods?
\q1 \add Well,\add* they’re not gods \add at all\add*!
\p
\v 21 \add So listen,\add* I’m about to \add demonstrate that\add* at this time—
\q1 I’ll reveal my power and activity to them
\q1 and then they’ll know that my name is Yahweh.
\c 17
\s1 Yehudah’s sin and punishment
\p
\v 1 Yehudah’s sin is written with an iron stylus that has a diamond point.
\q1 It’s engraved on the tablet which is their hearts, and on the projecting corners of your altars.
\q1
\v 2 Even their children remember their altars and their Asherah poles
\q1 that were beside the luxuriant trees and on the high hills—
\q1
\v 3 \add even on\add* my mountain in the countryside.
\q1 I’ll give your wealth and all your treasures \add to be plundered\add* \add by others\add*
\q1 \add because\add* of your sin on your \add hilltop shrines\add* throughout all your territories.
\q1
\v 4 You’ll \add have to let go\add* the inheritance that I gave you.
\q1 I’ll make your serve your enemies in a land that \add you’ve never been to\add*,
\q1 because you’ve ignited a fire in my anger which will burn forever.
\s1 Various sayings
\p
\v 5 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Anyone who trusts in humankind will be cursed—
\q1 trusting in their \add own physical strength\add* turns their \add hearts\add* away from Yahweh.
\q1
\v 6 They’re like shrubs in the desert, unable to see any good coming,
\q1 and they’ll live in dry parts of the wilderness
\q1 that’s salty and with no one \add else\add* living there.
\b
\q1
\v 7 The person who trusts in Yahweh will be blessed,
\q1 \add as\add* they put their confidence in \add him\add*.
\q1
\v 8 \add That person\add* will be like a tree planted by a stream\x + \xo 17:8: \xt Psa 1:3.\x*
\q1 that sends its roots out to the water.
\q1 It \add has nothing to fear\add* when the heat comes and its leaves stay green.
\q1 It has nothing to be afraid of in a drought year
\q1 and it won’t stop producing fruit.
\b
\q1
\v 9 \add Human motives\add* are the most deceitful of all.
\q1 \add They\add* can’t be cured—who can \add determine\add* \add them\add*?
\q1
\v 10 I am Yahweh who searches \add the mind\add*.
\q1 I test \add the motives\add*.
\q1 I give to everyone according to the \add results of their actions\add*.\x + \xo 17:10: a \xt Rev 2:23; \xo b \xt Psa 62:12.\x*
\b
\q1
\v 11 A partridge hatches an egg that it didn’t lay.
\q1 Someone \add might get rich by unjust means\add*
\q1 \add but right\add* in the middle of their \add life\add* it’ll leave them
\q1 and in the end, \add that person\add* will be a fool.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s request to Yahweh
\p
\v 12 The place of our sanctuary from the beginning has been \add like\add* a \add splendid\add* throne \add on\add* a high place.
\q1
\v 13 \add You,\add* Yahweh are \add the one that Yisrael puts their hope in\add*.
\q1 All who abandon you will be put to shame.
\q1 Those who turn away from you will be written on the ground,
\q1 because they’ve forsaken Yahweh—the fountain of living waters.
\q1
\v 14 Heal me, Yahweh, and I’ll be healed.
\q1 Rescue me, and I’ll be rescued,
\q1 because you are \add the one I\add* praise.
\q1
\v 15 Listen, they’re \add asking\add* me,
\q1 Where is Yahweh’s message? Let it come.
\q1
\v 16 \add As for me\add*, I didn’t run from being a shepherd following you.
\q1 I didn’t long for the day \add of disaster\add*.
\q1 You know \add everything I said\add*—it was \add said in your presence\add*.
\q1
\v 17 Don’t become a terror to me.
\q1 You’re my \add place of safety when disaster comes\add*.
\q1
\v 18 Let my pursuers be ashamed, but don’t let me be ashamed.
\q1 Ley them be dismayed, but don’t let me be dismayed.
\q1 Send the day of disaster against them
\q1 and \add shatter them with a double share of destruction\add*.
\s1 Observing the rest day
\p
\v 19 Yahweh told me this:
\q1 Go and stand in at gate of the people where Yehudah’s kings come and go,
\q1 then in all the \add other\add* gates of Yerushalem.
\q1
\v 20 Tell \add the people\add*:
\q1 Listen to Yahweh’s message, \add you\add* kings of Yehudah and all you \add people of\add* Yehudah,
\q1 and all of Yerushalem’s residents who go in through those gates.
\q1
\v 21 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Be careful \add for the sake of\add* your lives
\q1 and on the rest day, don’t carry a load to bring it to Yerushalem’s gates.\x + \xo 17:21: \xt Neh 13:15-22.\x*
\q1
\v 22 Don’t bring a load out from your homes on the rest day.
\q1 Don’t do any work, but set apart the rest day,
\q1 just as I instructed your ancestors to do.
\q1
\v 23 They did not listen or pay attention,
\q1 \add but stubbornly refused to listen to\add* me, nor did they accept discipline.
\p
\v 24 Yahweh declares that if you carefully listen to me
\q1 and don’t bring a load to this city’s gates on the rest day
\q1 but instead set apart the rest day for Yahweh, and don’t do any work on it,
\q1
\v 25 then kings, princes, and those who sit on David’s throne
\q1 will come to this city’s gates in chariots and on horses.
\q1 They’ll \add come\add* \add along with\add* their leaders from Yehudah \add including\add* Yerushalem’s residents,
\q1 and this city will \add be inhabited\add* forever.
\q1
\v 26 They’ll come from Yehudah’s cities \add including\add* from all around Yerushalem,
\q1 from the Benyamin region and the foothills,
\q1 from the mountains, and from the Negev \add desert\add*,
\q1 bringing burnt offerings and sacrifices, grain offerings and frankincense,
\q1 as well as those who bring thank offerings to Yahweh’s residence.
\q1
\v 27 \add But\add* if you don’t listen to me
\q1 \add and don’t\add* set apart the rest day
\q1 and don’t carry heavy loads to enter Yerushalem’s gates on the rest day,
\q1 then I’ll light a fire at its gates \add that\add* will \add incinerate\add* Yerushalem’s fortresses,
\q1 and that won’t be able to be put out.
\c 18
\s1 Yirmeyah visits the potter
\p
\v 1 Yahweh’s message came to Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add* to say,
\v 2 “\add Get ready\add* and go down to the potter’s house, and I’ll give you my messages there.”
\p
\v 3 \add So\add* I went down to \add pottery factory\add*, and wow, he was on his potter’s wheel.
\v 4 \add However,\add* the container that he was making with his hand on the clay was ruined, so he \add started again\add* and make it into another container that \add he was pleased with\add*.
\p
\v 5 Then Yahweh \add gave me this message\add*:
\v 6 Like that potter, shouldn’t I be able to do what I want with you \add Israelis\add*? Yahweh declares that you \add Israelis\add* are in my hand like that clay in the potter’s hand.
\v 7 \add One time\add*, I might declare to a nation or a kingdom that it will be uprooted, torn down, and destroyed.
\v 8 and \add later on,\add* that nation that I spoke to might turn away from its evil, and then I’ll \add cancel\add* the destruction that I’d planned for them.
\v 9 \add Another time,\add* I might declare that a nation or kingdom will be \add established\add*, or strengthened,
\v 10 \add however\add* if \add I see it\add* doing evil and not listening to my voice, then I’ll \add cancel\add* the good that I’d said I’d do to it.
\v 11 \add So\add* now, speak to the people of Yehudah \add including\add* Yerushalem’s residents and tell them that Yahweh says, “Listen, I’m about to devise a plan against you all and \add prepare\add* calamity for you. Each of you needs to turn back from their evil \add activities\add* and \add improve\add* your \add behaviour\add* and your \add activities\add*.”
\v 12 \add However,\add* they’ll say, “\add Don’t waste your time\add* because we’ll \add continue with\add* our plans, and each of us will do \add whatever\add* wicked \add things\add* that we want!”
\s1 Yisrael deserts Yahweh
\p
\v 13 \add Because of that,\add* Yahweh says this:
\q1 Ask the nations if they’ve \add ever heard anything like this\add*?
\q2 The virgin Yisrael \add (Israel)\add* has done \add something\add* extremely horrible.
\q1
\v 14 Does the snow in Lebanon ever \add disappear off\add* its \add rocky slopes\add*?
\q1 Do the cool waters \add stop flowing\add*?
\q1
\v 15 \add Yet\add* my people have forgotten me.
\q1 They \add offer incense\add* to \add useless idols\add*
\q1 that have made them stumble on the ancient paths
\q1 that haven’t \add had any maintenance\add*.
\q1
\v 16 Their land will become a wasteland—\add forever mocked at\add*.
\q1 Everyone who passes by will be appalled
\q1 and will wag \add their heads\add*.
\q1
\v 17 I’ll scatter them before their enemies like the east wind \add from the desert\add* does.
\q1 I \add won’t look at them but will turn\add* my back \add when their disaster comes\add*.
\s1 A plot against Yirmeyah
\sp The people
\p
\v 18 Then \add the people\add* said,
\q1 Come on, let’s \add decide what to do about\add* Yirmeyah,
\q1 because \add we have plenty of instructions\add* from the \add priests\add*,
\q1 advice from the wise \add men\add*,
\q1 and \add messages\add* from the \add prophets\add*.
\sp Yirmeyah
\p
\v 19 Yahweh, pay attention to me
\q1 and listen to the \add what my enemies are saying\add*.
\q1
\v 20 Should good be repaid with evil,
\q1 because they’re digging a pit for me?
\q1 Remember how I stood \add in front of\add* you to \add tell you their good points\add*—
\q1 to turn back your rage from them.
\q1
\v 21 Therefore, \add hand\add* their children over to famine,
\q1 and \add send war to punish\add* them.
\q1 Let their wives be childless and become widowed,
\q1 and let their husbands \add die from disease\add*—
\q1 their young men \add killed\add* in battle.
\q1
\v 22 Let a cry of distress be heard from their houses
\q1 \add when\add* you send raiders \add to surprise\add* them,
\q1 because they’ve dug a pit to capture me in
\q1 and have hidden traps for \add me to step into\add*.
\q1
\v 23 \add But\add* you, Yahweh, know all their \add deadly plots against\add* me.
\q1 Don’t \add forgive their wickedness\add*.
\q1 Don’t \add erase their disobedience from your sight\add*.
\q1 Let them be overthrown \add as you watch\add*
\q1 at the time \add when\add* you deal with them in your anger.
\c 19
\s1 The shattered flask
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh said this:
\q1 Take some of the elders and some of the priests,
\q1 and go and buy a clay flask from the potter.
\q1
\v 2 Then go out to the Ben-Hinnom Valley by the Broken Pottery Gate,
\q1 and then proclaim the words that I’ll tell you there.\x + \xo 19:2: \xt 2Ki 23:10; Jer 7:30-32; 32:34-35.\x*
\q1
\v 3 Tell \add them\add*:
\q1 You kings of Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* and \add you\add* residents of Yerushalem,
\q1 listen to Yahweh’s message.
\q1 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says,
\q1 Listen, I’m about to \add send\add* calamity to this place,
\q1 \add and\add* the ears of everyone who hears about it will tingle.
\q1
\v 4 \add I’m doing that\add* because they’ve abandoned me and \add defiled\add* this place—
\q1 they’ve \add burnt incense\add* to other ‘gods’,
\q1 that neither they or their ancestors or Yehudah’s kings used to know.
\q1 Then they’ve filled this place with the blood of the innocent.
\q1
\v 5 They built \add hilltop shrines\add* to burn their children in the fire as offerings to Baal,
\q1 something I never instructed or talked about, nor did it \add even\add* \add enter my mind\add*.\x + \xo 19:5: \xt Lev 18:21.\x*
\p
\v 6 So Yahweh declares that the time is coming when this place will no longer be called Tofet or the Valley of Ben-Hinnom, but \add rather\add*, the ‘Valley of Slaughter’.
\v 7 Then I’ll confound Yehudah and Yerushalem’s plans in this place, and I’ll \add have them struck down by their enemies’ swords\add* and by those who \add want to kill them\add*, and I’ll give their dead bodies to the birds and the wild animals for food.
\v 8 Then I’ll make that city into a wasteland \add that’s something to scoff at\add*—everyone who passes by will be appalled and will \add mock it because of all its disasters\add*.
\v 9 I’ll cause them to eat the flesh of their children and of their neighbours \add during the distress caused by the siege imposed by the enemies who want to kill them\add*.
\p
\v 10 Then as the men who went with you \add watch\add*, you must break that pottery flask
\v 11 and tell them that Commander-in_chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 I’ll shatter this \add nation\add* and this city, just like someone shatters a \add piece of pottery\add* that can never be repaired again. They’ll bury \add the dead\add* in Tofet until \add they run out of\add* room.
\v 12 Yahweh declares that I’ll do that to this place and its residents—making this city like Tofet
\v 13 and Yerushalem’s houses \add including\add* the houses of Yehudah’s kings will be defiled like that place, Tofet—all the houses on whose rooftops they burned incense to all the \add constellations\add* and poured out drink offerings to other ‘gods’.
\p
\v 14 Then Yirmeyah returned from Tofet where Yahweh had sent him to prophesy, and he stood in the \add temple\add* courtyard and proclaimed to all the people,
\v 15 “This is what Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh, says: ‘Listen, every disaster that I’ve pronounced against \add these people\add*, I’m about to \add send\add* to this city and to all the villages around it, because they’ve \add been stubborn and failed to take notice\add* of my messages.’ ”
\c 20
\s1 Yirmeyah’s conflict with Pashhur
\p
\v 1 The priest, Pashhur (Immer’s son) who was a supervisor, heard Yirmeyah prophesying those words at Yahweh’s house,
\v 2 and he struck the prophet Yirmeyah. Then he placed him in the stocks that were at the upper gate of Benyamin \add hear\add* Yahweh’s house.
\v 3 The next day, when \add Pashhur\add* released Yirmeyah from the stocks, Yirmeyah said to him, “Yahweh won’t call you ‘Pashhur’, but ‘Magor-Missabib’ \add (which means ‘surrounded by terror’)\add*,
\v 4 because Yahweh says this: Listen, I’ll make you a terror to yourself and to all your friends. They’ll fall by their enemies’ \add swords\add* before your very eyes, and then I’ll hand Yehudah over to the Babylonian king, and he’ll carry them away to Babylon and put them to \add death\add*.
\v 5 I’ll give away all the wealth of this city—all its products and valuables, and all the treasures of Yehudah’s kings—to their enemies. They’ll plunder it, seize it, and carry it off to Babylon.
\v 6 Then you, Pashhur will \add be taken\add* into captivity \add along with all the others in your home\add*. You’ll \add be taken\add* to Babylon, and you’ll die there and be buried—you and all your friends who you’ve prophesied these lies to.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s complaint to Yahweh
\q1
\v 7 Yahweh, you’ve deceived me, and I was deceived.
\q1 You’ve overcome me and prevailed.
\q1 I’m \add laughed at\add* all day long—
\q1 everyone mocks me.
\b
\q1
\v 8 \add Yes,\add* whenever I speak, I \add call out loudly\add*.
\q1 I proclaim violence and destruction
\q1 because Yahweh’s message has become a reproach and derision for me, all day \add long\add*.
\q1
\v 9 If I say that I won’t \add mention\add* him
\q1 and won’t speak in his name anymore,
\q1 then \add his message\add* becomes a fire burning in my heart—
\q1 shut up in my bones.
\q1 Then I \add get worn out\add* holding it in,
\q1 and I can’t continue \add to do it\add*.
\q1
\v 10 \add Yes,\add* I’ve heard many \add people\add* whispering
\q1 that terror is all around.
\q1 \add They want to publicly denounce me\add*.
\q1 All my trusted friends watch for my fall:
\q1 “Perhaps he can be deceived
\q1 so that we may prevail against him
\q1 and take out our vengeance on him.”
\q1
\v 11 \add However\add* Yahweh is like a fearsome warrior with me,
\q1 therefore \add my persecutors\add* will stumble and won’t prevail.
\q1 Because they won’t succeed, they’ll be totally put to shame—
\q1 an everlasting disgrace that’ll never be forgotten.
\q1
\v 12 Commander-in-chief Yahweh, who examines the righteous \add people\add*,
\q1 who sees the \add thoughts and motives\add*,
\q1 let me see your vengeance upon them,
\q1 →because I’ve made my case known to you.
\q1
\v 13 Sing to Yahweh.
\q1 Praise Yahweh because he’s rescued the lives of \add those who are oppressed\add* from the \add clutch\add* of \add those who do evil\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 14 Let the day when I was born be cursed.\x + \xo 20:14-18: \xt Yob 3:1-19.\x*
\q1 Don’t let the day that my mother \add gave birth to me\add* be blessed.
\q1
\v 15 Let the man who brought the news to my father be cursed—
\q1 The one who said, ‘You now have a son,’ causing great celebration.
\q1
\v 16 Let that man be like the cities that Yahweh overthrew \add without having\add* compassion on them.
\q1 Let him hear a cry for help in the dawn and a battle cry at noontime,
\q1
\v 17 because he didn’t kill me in the womb—
\q1 →making my mother become my tomb—her womb forever pregnant.
\q1
\v 18 Why did I come out from the womb to see trouble and sorrow,
\q1 and to end my days in shame?
\c 21
\s1 Yerushalem’s future destruction
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh \add gave\add* Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add* a meesage when King Tsidkiyah \add (Zedekiah)\add* sent Malkiyah’s son Pashhur and Maaseyah’s son Tsefanyah \add (Zephaniah)\add* the priest to him, and they said,
\v 2 “Please \add request\add* Yahweh’s advice on our behalf, because the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar is \add attacking\add* us. Perhaps Yahweh will do miracles for us like \add he has in the past\add*, and will make him \add stop attacking us and leave\add*.”\x + \xo 21:2: \xt 2Ki 25:1-11; 2Ch 36:17-21.\x*
\p
\v 3 \add So\add* Yirmeyah told them to tell \add King\add* Tsidkiyah that
\v 4 Yisrael’s god Yahweh says this:
\m Listen, I’m about to \add make your own weapons ineffective\add* that you’re all using to fight the Babylonian king and the Babylonians \add (Heb. Kasdi = Chaldeans)\add* who are laying siege to you from outside the wall, and I’ll gather them\f + \fr 21:4 \ft This last part of the sentence is left quite literal, as it’s ambiguous in the Hebrew, what or who the ‘them’ is referring to here.\f* in the middle of this city.
\v 5 Then I myself will fight you all \add with all my strength and power\add* in my anger and rage and terrible fury,
\v 6 and I’ll \add kill\add* this city’s inhabitants—people and animals will all die in a \add terrible\add* plague.
\v 7 Then Yahweh declares that after that I’ll hand over Yehudah’s King Tsidkiyah \add along with\add* his officers, and the people in this city who survive the plague and sword and famine, to the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar, and to their enemies who \add want to kill them\add*. He’ll \add kill them with\add* the sword—he won’t spare them or show pity or compassion.
\p
\v 8 Then you must tell this to the people:
\m Yahweh says that I’m \add about to give you the choice between\add* the path to life and the path to death.
\v 9 Anyone who stays in this city will die from \add war\add*, famine, or plague, but anyone who goes out and falls to their knees in front of the Babylonians who’ve surrounded you all, will live They’ll escape with their lives \add that way\add*
\v 10 because I’ve \add already decided\add* to harm this city \add rather than doing good\add*. Yahweh declares that \add this city\add* will be \add handed over\add* to the Babylonian king and he’ll burn it \add down\add*.
\s1 Yahweh’s punishment for Yehudah’s kings
\p
\v 11 As for Yehudah’s king, listen to this message from Yahweh
\v 12 for David’s descendants:
\q1 Administer justice \add every\add* morning
\q1 and rescue anyone who’s been robbed, from their oppressor,
\q1 otherwise my fury will go out like fire
\q1 and burn, \add but\add* no one will be able to extinguish it
\q1 because of your wicked activities.
\q1
\v 13 Yahweh declares: listen you inhabitants from the valley
\q1 \add and you\add* on the rocky plain.
\q1 You all say \add that no one\add* can \add swoop\add* down on you,
\q1 or \add be able to\add* enter your hiding places,
\q1
\v 14 \add however\add* I will \add punish\add* you all according to the \add results\add* of your actions.
\q1 Yahweh declares:
\q1 I’ll \add start\add* a fire in your forest
\q1 and it’ll consume everything around it.
\c 22
\s1 The message for Yehudah’s king
\p
\v 1 Yahweh told \add me\add* to go down to Yehudah’s \add palace\add* and proclaim this message:
\v 2 Listen to Yahweh’s message for Yehudah’s king who sits on David’s throne, \add along with\add* your officials and your people who enter these \add doorways\add*.
\v 3 Yahweh says \add that you must\add* administer justice and \add do what’s right\add*. Rescue anyone who’s been robbed, from their oppressor. Don’t mistreat any foreigner or orphan or widow. Don’t be violent, and don’t shed innocent blood in this place,
\v 4 because if you carefully do those things, then the kings who sit on David’s throne will enter through the gates of this palace riding in chariots or on horses, \add along with\add* their officials and their people.
\v 5 \add However,\add* if you \add take no notice\add* of those \add instructions\add*, then Yahweh \add solemnly promises\add* that this \add palace\add* will become a \add pile of rubble\add*,\x + \xo 22:5: \xt Mat 23:28; Luk 13:35.\x*
\v 6 because this is what Yahweh says about the \add palace\add* of Yehudah’s king:
\q1 To me, you’re like the Gilead \add forests\add* or like Lebanon’s \add summit\add*.
\q1 \add However,\add* I’ll make you into a wilderness—
\q1 cities that aren’t inhabited.
\q1
\v 7 I’ll \add appoint\add* destroyers against you—
\q1 each \add warrior\add* with his weapons.
\q1 They’ll cut down your choicest cedars
\q1 and throw them onto the fire.
\p
\v 8 Then many nations will pass by this city and \add ask each\add* other why Yahweh has done that to this great city?
\v 9 \add Someone else will answer that it’s because\add* they abandoned the agreement with their god Yahweh, and bowed down to ther gods and served them.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s message about King Yoshiyah/Josiah
\q1
\v 10 Don’t weep for \add King Yoshiyah\add* \add (Josiah)\add* \add who was killed\add*
\q1 and don’t mourn \add because he died\add*.
\q1 \add Instead,\add* weep bitterly for \add his son, King Yehoahaz\add* \add (Jehoahaz)\add* who’s about to be exiled
\q1 because he won’t return again and see his native land \add again\add*.
\p
\v 11 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh says this about Yoshiyah’s son Yehoahaz\f + \fr 22:11 \ft Called ‘Shallum’ here in the Hebrew.\f* who reigned instead of his father, who \add then\add* left this place. He won’t return there again\x + \xo 22:11: \xt 2Ki 23:31-34; 2Ch 36:1-4.\x*
\v 12 because he’ll die in the place where they took him into exile, and he won’t \add ever\add* see this country again.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s message about Yehoyakim/Jehoiakim
\s4 Southern kingdom
\q1
\v 13 The \add king\add*\f + \fr 22:13 \ft Referring here to Yehudah’s King Yehoyakim (Jehoiakim)—see verse 24.\f* who built his house \add by doing what’s not right\add*
\q1 and \add built\add* his upper rooms \add by unjustly\add* \add forcing people to work\add*,
\q1 →won’t end well.
\q1 He forced the citizens to work without \add getting paid\add*—
\q1 not giving them their wages.
\q1
\v 14 He’d \add decided to\add* build himself a large house with spacious upper rooms,
\q1 \add so\add* he cut out large windows for it, and panelled it with cedar,
\q1 and \add painted\add* it with red \add ochre\add*.
\q1
\v 15 \add Does having the best\add* cedar make you a \add better\add* king?
\q1 Didn’t \add (Yoshiyah/Josiah)\add* your father eat and drink \add well\add*?
\q1 \add However,\add* he \add administered\add* justice and \add did what was right\add*
\q1 →\add so\add* \add things went\add* well for him.
\q1
\v 16 He \add took up\add* the cause of the poor and needy,
\q1 →\add so\add* \add things went\add* well for him.
\q1 Yahweh declares that \add that’s what it means to know\add* me,
\q1
\v 17 \add but\add* your \add desires and motives\add* are \add only focussed on\add* your dishonest gain,
\q1 on shedding innocent blood,
\q1 and on oppression and \add practicing\add* extortion.
\p
\v 18 Therefore this is what Yahweh says about Yehoyakim \add (Jehoiakim)\add*, son of Yehudah’s King Yoshiyah \add (Josiah)\add*:
\q1 They won’t mourn for him \add saying,\add* ‘Oh no, my brother! Oh no, my sister!’
\q1 They won’t mourn for him \add saying,\add* ‘Oh no, my master! Oh no, his splendour!’\x + \xo 22:18: \xt 2Ki 23:36–24:6; 2Ch 36:5-7.\x*
\q1
\v 19 He’ll be buried \add just like a donkey would be\add*—
\q1 dragged away and thrown \add somewhere\add* outside Yerushalem’s gates.
\s1 Yirmeyah’s message about Yerushalem’s fate
\q1
\v 20 \add You people of Yehudah,\add* go up to Lebanon and cry out.
\q1 \add Shout\add* in the Bashan \add region\add*.
\q1 Cry out from the Avarim \add mountains\add*,
\q1 because all your ‘lovers’ have been \add destroyed\add*.
\q1
\v 21 I \add warned\add* you \add when you were still secure\add*—
\q1 you said that \add you\add* wouldn’t listen.
\q1 That’s been your way since your youth,
\q1 that you haven’t \add taken any notice of my instructions\add*.
\q1
\v 22 The wind will \add drive away\add* all your ‘shepherds’,
\q1 and your ‘lovers’ will go into captivity.
\q1 Then you’ll be ashamed and humiliated \add because of\add* all your wickedness.
\q1
\v 23 \add You\add* who live in Lebanon,
\q1 nested \add there\add* among the cedars,
\q1 \add but\add* how you’ll groan when your labour pains come to you,
\q1 like \add a woman\add* giving birth.
\s1 Judgement for Yehoyakin/Jehoiachin
\p
\v 24 Yahweh declares by his life:
\m Even if \add you\add*, Yehoyakin \add (Jehoiachin)\add*,\f + \fr 22:24 \ft Called ‘Shallum’ here in the Hebrew and in verse 28.\f* son of Yehudah’s King Yehoyakim \add (Jehoiakim)\add*, were the signet ring on my right hand, I would tear you off\x + \xo 22:24: \xt 2Ki 24:8-15; 2Ch 36:9-10.\x*
\v 25 because I’m \add handing you over\add* to the \add ones\add* who are \add wanting to kill you\add* and to those that you’re afraid of—to Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar and \add his men\add*.\add (Heb. The Kasdi = Chaldeans)\add*
\v 26 I’ll hurl you and your mother who bore you, into another land—a country where \add you’re both foreigners\add* and you’ll both die there.
\v 27 \add Although\add* they’ll long to return to \add this\add* land, they’ll \add never\add* return here.
\p
\v 28 Is this man \add Yehoyakin\add* a despised, shattered pot—
\q1 a jar that no one wants
\q1 Why will before hurled out \add along with\add* his descendants,
\q1 and thtown into a \add country that they’re not familiar with\add*?
\q1
\v 29 Land, land, land, Listen to Yahweh’s message.
\p
\v 30 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Record this man as being childless—
\q1 a man who won’t prosper in his \add lifetime\add*.
\q1 None of his descendants will prosper
\q1 to sit on David’s throne
\q1 or to rule over Yehudah again.
\c 23
\s1 Returning under new shepherds
\p
\v 1 Yahweh declares that the shepherds who destroy and scatter the flock from my pasture \add won’t end well\add*.
\v 2 Therefore, this is what Yisrael’s god Yahweh says about the shepherds who tend My people: Yahweh declares that you’ve all scattered my flock and driven them away, and haven’t \add looked after\add* them. Listen, I’m about to \add punish\add* you all for your wicked actions.
\v 3 Then I myself will gather the remnant of my flock from all the \add countries\add* that I’ve banished them to and I’ll return them to their pasture, where they’ll be fruitful and multiply.
\v 4 Yahweh declares that I’ll \add appoint\add* shepherds over them who’ll \add look after\add* them, and then they’ll no longer be afraid or dismayed, nor will any go missing.
\v 5 Listen, Yahweh declares that the \add time is\add* coming
\q1 when I will \add appoint\add* a righteous branch for David
\q1 and he will reign wisely as king
\q1 and will \add administer\add* justice and righteousness in the land.\x + \xo 23:5-6: \xt Jer 33:14-16.\x*
\q1
\v 6 \add At that time\add*, Yehudah will be rescued and Yisrael will live in security,
\q1 and this is the name that he’ll be \add known by\add*: Yahweh \add who does what is right for us\add*.
\p
\v 7 Listen, Yahweh declares that the \add time is\add* coming when they’ll no longer say, ‘As surely as Yahweh lives, who brought the \add Israelis\add* out from Egypt.’
\v 8 \add Instead\add* \add they’ll say\add*, ‘As surely as Yahweh lives, who brought and led the \add Israelis\add* out of the land in the north and all the other lands that he’d banished them to.’ Then they’ll live in their own land again.
\s1 Lying prophets
\q1
\v 9 As for the prophets,
\q1 \add I feel broken inside\add* and all my bones tremble.
\q1 I’ve become like a drunkard—like a man overcome by wine,
\q1 because of Yahweh—because of his holy words.
\q1
\v 10 \add Yes,\add* the land is full of adulterers—
\q1 the land mourns because of the curse,
\q1 and the pastures in the wilderness have dried up—
\q1 their course is evil and their \add power is misused\add*.
\q1
\v 11 \add Yes,\add* both prophet and priest are \add compromised\add*—
\q1 even in my house I’ve discovered their wickedness.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 12 Therefore their path will become slippery.
\q1 They’ll be pushed into the darkness and will fall into it
\q1 because I’ll \add send them disaster\add* in the year of their punishment.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 13 Among the prophets in Shomrom \add (Samaria)\add*, I’ve seen \add offensive behaviour\add*:
\q1 they prophesied by Baal and led my people Yisrael astray.
\q1
\v 14 Also, among the prophets in Yerushalem, I’ve seen horrible things:\x + \xo 23:14: \xt Gen 18:20; Eze 16:49.\x*
\q1 They commit adultery and walk in lies.
\q1 They \add empower those who do evil\add*,
\q1 →so that no one turns their back on wickedness.
\q1 They’re all like Sodom to me.
\q1 The people in Jerusalem are like Gomorrah,
\q1
\v 15 therefore this is what Commander-in-chief Yahweh says about the prophets:
\q1 I’ll feed them wormwood
\q1 and give them poisoned water to drink,
\q1 because ungodliness has spread throughout the land
\q1 \add starting from\add* Yerushalem’s prophets.
\p
\v 16 This is what Commander-in-chief Yahweh says:
\q1 Don’t listen to the words of the prophets who prophesy to you.
\q1 They are filling you all with false hopes.
\q1 They speak visions from their own minds,
\q1 not from Yahweh’s mouth.
\q1
\v 17 They keep telling those who despise me,
\q1 that Yahweh says that you’ll all have peace.
\q1 \add They tell\add* everyone who \add practises their own stubborn ways\add*
\q1 that no harm will come to \add them\add*.
\p
\v 18 \add But\add* which of them has \add attended\add* Yahweh’s council \add meeting\add*
\q1 \add where he could\add* see \add what’s happening\add* and hear his message?
\q1 Who has paid attention to his message and \add obeyed it\add*?
\q1
\v 19 Listen, the storm of Yahweh’s rage is going out,
\q1 and the storm is \add creating a whirlwind\add* that’s whirling around the heads of \add those who are\add* wicked.
\q1
\v 20 Yahweh’s anger won’t turn back until he’s carried out his \add plans and\add* purposes.
\q1 In the \add final\add* days, you’ll all understand it.
\p
\v 21 I didn’t send \add those\add* prophets, yet they \add rushed\add* \add to proclaim their messages\add*.
\q1 I didn’t speak to them, \add yet\add* they \add still\add* prophesied.
\q1
\v 22 If they had \add in fact\add* \add attended\add* my council \add meeting\add*,
\q1 they would have proclaimed my messages to my people
\q1 and turned them back from their \add wickedness and their wicked activities\add*.
\p
\v 23 Yahweh declares:
\q1 Am I a god who’s only nearby, \add but\add* who isn’t \add also\add* a god from \add far away\add*?
\q1
\v 24 Would someone hide themself in some place and \add think\add* that I couldn’t see them? Yahweh \add asks\add*.
\q1 Don’t I fill the heavens and the earth? declares Yahweh.
\p
\v 25 Those prophets who prophesy lies in my name, I’ve heard them say, ‘I \add had a dream\add*. I \add had a dream\add*!’
\v 26 How long will this go on, with prophets who prophesy lies from their own \add minds\add*, but who are prophesying from the deceitfulness of their own \add hearts\add*.
\v 27 They’re planning on making my people forget my name with the dreams that they report, each one to his neighbour, just as their ancestors forgot my name in favour of Baal’s name.
\v 28 Let the prophet who has a dream, report \add that\add* dream. \add However,\add* the \add one\add* who I’ve declared something to, let him declare my message truthfully. What does straw have to do with grain? That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 29 Isn’t my message like fire, and like a hammer that shatters rock? That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 30 So listen, Yahweh declares that I’m against the prophets who steal my messages from \add someone else\add*.
\v 31 \add Yes,\add* I’m against \add those\add* prophets who \add speak their own messages by claim that the messages came from me\add*.
\v 32 Yahweh declares that \add indeed\add*, I’m against those who prophesy false dreams and retell them to lead my people astray with their reckless lies. It wasn’t me who sent or commanded them, and they’re of no benefit at all to those people. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 False prophets
\p
\v 33 \add Now\add* when this people \add group\add* or a prophet or priest asks you, ‘What is Yahweh’s burden?’\f + \fr 23:33 \ft The Hebrew word translated ‘burden’ could alternatively mean ‘message of doom’ here and through to verse 40, except that it’s also used to describe the people.\f* you \add should\add* tell them, ‘\add You are the\add* burden and I’ll abandon you.’ That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 34 As for the prophet \add or\add* priest \add or\add* anyone who claims that he \add knows\add* Yahweh’s burden, I’ll punish that man and his household.
\v 35 This is what each of you should \add ask\add* their friend or relative: ‘What did Yahweh answer?’ or ‘What has Yahweh said?’
\v 36 \add But\add* don’t refer anymore to Yahweh’s burden, because each person’s message becomes the burden, so you all \add end up\add* perverting the words of the living god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh, our god.
\v 37 This is what you \add should ask\add* to the prophet, ‘What answer did Yahweh give you?’ or ‘What did Yahweh say?’
\v 38 \add However\add* if you say, ‘Yahweh’s burden’, then this is what Yahweh says: Because you said those words, ‘Yahweh’s burden,’ \add after\add* I sent you all \add a message\add* saying, ‘Don’t say, “Yahweh’s burden,’
\v 39 therefore listen, I’ll definitely forget you and will remove you all \add out of my presence\add*—both you and your ancestors, and the city that I gave you.
\v 40 Then I’ll put permanent shame on you all, and \add continual insults\add* that won’t be forgotten.
\c 24
\s1 Two baskets of figs
\s4 Southern kingdom
\p
\v 1 After the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar had carried away Yehoyakin \add (Jehoiakim, Heb. Yekonyah = Jeconiah)\add*, son of Yehudah’s King Yehoyakim \add (Jehoiakim)\add*, as well as Yehudah’s officials and Yerushalem’s craftsmen and metalsmiths, and had taken them to Babylon, Yahweh showed me two baskets of figs placed in front of \add his\add* temple.\x + \xo 24:1: \xt 2Ki 24:12-16; 2Ch 36:10.\x*
\v 2 One basket of figs was very good like early, ripe figs, but the figs in the other basket were so bad that they \add weren’t edible\add*.
\v 3 Then Yahweh asked me, “Yirmeyah, what do you see?”
\p “Figs,” I \add replied\add*. “\add Some\add* figs that \add look\add* very good, and \add others\add* that are so bad \add they’re inedible\add*.”
\p
\v 4 Then Yahweh \add gave\add* me this message:
\v 5 Yisrael’s god, Yahweh, says this: I’ll look favourably at the exiles from Yehudah just like those good figs, the exiles that I’ve sent out from this place to Babylonia.
\v 6 I’ll \add give them my favour\add* and restore them to this land. I’ll build them up, and not tear them down. I’ll plant them, and not uproot them.
\v 7 Then I will give them a \add desire\add* to know me, because I’m Yahweh. They’ll be my people and I will be their god, so they will turn to me \add wholeheartedly\add*.
\p
\v 8 \add But\add* Yahweh declares that \add just\add* like \add those\add* bad figs that are \add inedible\add* \add will be discarded\add*, I’ll act in that \add same\add* way towards Yehudah’s King Zedekiah, along with his officials and the rest of Yerushalem who remain in this land or go to stay in the land of Egypt.
\v 9 I’ll turn them into something horrifying—a disaster, \add right there\add* in the sight of all the world’s kingdoms—a disgrace and a subject for proverbs, taunts, and curses in every place that I’ll drive them into.
\v 10 I’ll send \add armies\add*, famine, and \add disease\add* against them until they’re destroyed from the land that I gave to them and their ancestors.
\c 25
\s1 Exile to Babylon foretold
\p
\v 1 This is the message that came to Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add* concerning all the people of Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* in the fourth year of \add the reign of\add* Yehoyakim (\add Jehoiakim,\add* son of Yehudah’s King Yoshiyah \add (Josiah)\add*), which was the first year of \add the reign of\add* the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar.
\v 2 The prophet Yirmeyah proclaimed this to all the people \add across\add* Yehudah \add including\add* all of Yerushalem’s inhabitants, saying:
\v 3 Yahweh’s messages have been coming to me for twenty-three years since the thirteenth year of the reign of Yehudah’s king Yoshiyah (\add Josiah,\add* Amon’s son), and I’ve \add passed them on\add* to you all \add over and over again\add*, \add but\add* you haven’t \add taken any notice\add* \add of them\add*.
\v 4 Yahweh sent all his servants the prophets to you again and again, but you all haven’t listened \add or paid any attention\add*.
\v 5 \add Those prophets\add* said, ‘Let everyone turn from their wicked ways and their evil activities, and return to the land that Yahweh gave in ancient times to your ancestors and to all of you as a permanent \add inheritance\add*.
\v 6 \add So\add* don’t walk after other gods to worship them or to bow down to them, and don’t provoke \add him\add* with \add things you make with\add* your hands, and then \add he\add* won’t harm you all.’
\v 7 \add But\add* Yahweh declares that you all haven’t listened to me, \add because with what you’ve made\add*, you’ve provoked me to do harm to you.
\p
\v 8 So Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this: Since all of you haven’t listen to my messages,
\v 9 listen, I’m about to send out a command to fetch all the northern peoples. Yahweh declares that I will bring my servant, the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar and \add his armies\add* against this land and its inhabitants, and against all the nations around you. I will \add mark\add* them for destruction and turn them into a horror—\add something to be hissed at\add*, and permanent ruins.
\v 10 I’ll put an end to the sounds of gladness and \add celebration\add*, the sounds of \add brides\add* and \add grooms\add*, \add and\add* the sound of the millstones and the light of the lamp.\x + \xo 25:10: a \xt Jer 7:34; 16:9; \xo b \xt Rev 18:22-23.\x*
\v 11 Then all of this land will become a desolation and a horror, and these nations will serve the Babylonian king for seventy years.\x + \xo 25:11: \xt 2Ch 36:21; Jer 29:10; Dan 9:2.\x*
\p
\v 12 Then after seventy years have \add passed\add*, then I’ll punish the king of Babylon and that nation—the land of the Chaldeans—for their wickedness, and make it into a permanent wasteland. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 13 Then I’ll carry out all the messages that I’d spoken against that land, and everything written in this document that Yirmeyah has prophesied against all the nations.
\v 14 \add Yes\add* many other nations and great kings will also make slaves out of those nations. I’ll repay them for \add everything they’ve done\add*.
\s1 The punishment of God of nations
\p
\v 15 \add Yes\add* Yisrael’s god Yahweh told me, “Take this cup of the wine of fury from my hand, and all the nations that I’m sending you to, make them drink it.
\v 16 They’ll drink and then stagger around and act like mad \add people\add* \add when they see the deadly army\add* that I’m sending out to them.
\p
\v 17 \add So\add* I took the cup from Yahweh’s hand and made all the nations that \add he’d\add* sent me to, drink from it,
\v 18 \add as well as\add* Yehudah’s cities \add including\add* Yerushalem and its \add king\add* and officials—to turn them into ruins and something terrifying, and into \add something to hiss and curse at\add*, as they are until this present day.
\v 19 \add Those nations included:\add*
\li1 Egypt’s King Far’oh \add (Pharaoh)\add*, his officials, his leaders, and all his people,
\li1
\v 20 all people of mixed heritage and all the kings of the land of Uts,
\li1 all the kings of the land of Philistia: Ashkelon, Azzah \add (Gaza)\add*, Ekron, and the remnant from Ashdod,
\li1
\v 21 Edom, Moav, and the Ammonites,
\li1
\v 22 all the kings of Tsor \add (Tyre)\add* and Tsidon \add (Sidon)\add*,
\li1 the kings from the coastlands across the sea,
\li1
\v 23 Dedan, Tema, Buz,
\li1 and all who cut the corners \add of their hair\add*,
\li1
\v 24 all the Arabian kings,
\li1 and all the kings of the mixed tribes who live in the desert,
\li1
\v 25 all the kings from Zimri, Elam, and Media,
\li1
\v 26 all the kings of the north, both near and far, one after another,
\li1 all the kingdoms \add around the world\add*.
\p And after all of them, the Babylonian\f + \fr 25:26 \ft ‘Babylon’ here in the Hebrew is ‘Sheshak’, which is Hebrew for ‘Babylon’ with the letters substituted in a simple code.\f* king will drink \add it too\add*.
\p
\v 27 Then Yahweh told me to tell them, ‘Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh, says this: Drink and become drunk, then vomit, fall down, and don’t get up \add again\add* \add until the deadly army arrives\add* that I’m sending among you.’
\v 28 Then if any \add of the above\add* refuse to take the cup from your hand to drink, tell me, ‘Commander-in-chief Yahweh says that you certainly must drink it,
\v 29 because listen, I’m about to bring disaster to the city that is called by my name, and should you yourselves be free from punishment? You won’t be free, because I’m calling a \add deadly army\add* against all the inhabitants of the land.’
\m That is Commander-in-chief Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 30 You must prophesy all these messages against them, telling them:
\q1 ‘Yahweh will roar from the heights
\q1 and he’ll \add shout\add* with his voice from his sacred residence,
\q1 and he will roar mightily against his \add land\add*,
\q1 and he will shout, like those who tread \add grapes in a wine-pressing pit\add*
\q1 against all those who live on the earth.
\q1
\v 31 The uproar will \add be heard even at\add* the ends of the earth
\q1 because Yahweh brings a charge against the nations.
\q1 He \add will pass\add* judgment on all humankind
\q1 and \add have the wicked killed in war\add*.
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 32 Commander-in-chief says this:
\q1 Listen, disaster is spreading from nation to nation.
\q1 A \add terrible\add* storm is rising from the ends of the earth.
\m
\v 33 Then those killed that day by Yahweh will be spread from \add one\add* end of the earth to the other. They won’t be mourned \add over\add*, gathered, or buried—they’ll be like dung lying on the ground.
\p
\v 34 Wail, \add you\add* shepherds, and call out for help.
\q1 Roll around in the dust, \add you\add* leaders of the flock,
\q1 because the \add time\add* has come for your slaughter.
\q1 You’ll all be scattered when you fall, like \add fragments of broken\add* pottery.
\q1
\v 35 There’s no safe place for the shepherds \add to go to\add*.
\q1 There’ll be no escape for the leaders of the flock.
\q1
\v 36 Hear the shepherds’ cries of distrress
\q1 and the wails of the leaders of the flock,
\q1 →because Yahweh is destroying their \add pastures\add*.
\q1
\v 37 So the peaceful pastures will be devastated
\q1 \add because of\add* Yahweh’s \add fierce\add* anger.
\q1
\v 38 He’s left his den like a young lion would,
\q1 because their land will become a horror
\q1 due to the oppressor’s anger and \add Yahweh’s\add* fierce angry.
\c 26
\s1 Wanting a death sentence for Yirmeyah
\p
\v 1 \add Near\add* the beginning of the reign of Yehoyakim \add (Jehoiakim, Yoshiyah’s\add*/Josiah’s son), this message came from Yahweh:
\v 2 Yahweh says this: Stand in the courtyard of my \add temple\add* and speak about all of Yehudah’s cities who come to worship at my \add residence\add*. Proclaim all the messages that I’ve commanded you to say to them—don’t hold \add anything\add* back.
\v 3 Maybe they’ll listen and everyone will turn from \add their wicked ways\add*, and then I would turn back the disaster that I’m planning to \add send\add* to them because of their wicked \add behaviour\add*,
\v 4 \add so\add* you \add need to\add* tell them that Yahweh says this:
\m If you don’t listen to me so as to \add follow my instructions that I’ve given to\add* you all,
\v 5 \add if you don’t\add* listen to the words of my servants the prophets that I’ve been \add regularly\add* sending to you, and \add indeed\add* you haven’t listened,
\v 6 then I’ll \add destroy\add* this house like \add I did at\add* Shiloh\x + \xo 26:6: \xt Josh 18:1; Psa 78:60; Jer 7:12-14.\x* and I’ll turn this city into a curse to/for all the nations \add in the world\add*.
\p
\v 7 The priests, the prophets, and all the people heard Yirmeyah proclaiming those words at Yahweh’s \add temple\add*.
\v 8 Then as soon as Yirmeyah had finished saying everything that Yahweh had commanded him to tell all the people, the priests and the prophets and all the people seized him \add and threatened to kill him, saying\add*:
\v 9 Why have you prophesied in Yahweh’s name and said that this \add temple\add* will be \add destroyed\add* like Shiloh, and that this city will become desolate, with no \add inhabitants\add*?” Then all the people \add gathered together\add* against Yirmeyah at Yahweh’s \add residence\add*.
\p
\v 10 Then Yehudah’s officials heard \add about what was going on\add*, and they went up from the \add palace\add* to \add the temple where\add* they sat in the gateway at the New Gate at Yahweh’s \add residence\add*.
\v 11 Then the priests and the prophets spoke to the officials and to all the people, saying, “It’s right for this man to die, because he prophesied against this city, as you’ve all heard with your own ears.”
\p
\v 12 \add So\add* Yirmeyah spoke to all the officials and all the people and said, “Yahweh has sent me out to prophesy to say all the words that you have heard, against \add both\add* this \add temple\add* and this city.
\v 13 \add So now,\add* improve your ways and your \add practices\add*, and listen to the voice of your god Yahweh so that he’ll relent concerning the disaster that he’s proclaimed against you all.
\v 14 \add As for me,\add* here I am in your \add hands\add*—do to me \add whatever you think\add* is right and proper.
\v 15 \add However,\add* you must surely know that if you kill me, then you’re all bringing innocent blood on yourselves and on this city and its inhabitants, because Yahweh has truly sent me to you to proclaim all these messages for you all \add to hear\add*.”
\p
\v 16 Then the officials and all the people said to the priests and to the prophets, “This man \add doesn’t deserve to be sentenced to\add* death, because he’s spoken to us in the name of our god, Yahweh.”
\p
\v 17 Then \add some\add* of \add Yehudah’s\add* elders \add stepped forward\add* and spoke to all the people who were gathered there,
\v 18 “Micah (\add Heb. Mikah,\add* the Morashtite) prophesied \add during the lifetime\add* of Yehudah’s King Hizkiyah\add (Hezekiah)\add*, and he told all the people from Yehudah that Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this:
\q1 Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*, a field will be ploughed,
\q1 and Yerushalem will become heaps \add of ruins\add*,
\q1 and the \add temple\add* hill will become an \add overgrown\add* forest.\x + \xo 26:18: \xt Mic 3:12.\x*
\m
\v 19 Did Yehudah’s King Hizkiyah or anyone else in Yehudah put him to death? Didn’t \add Hizkiyah\add* \add respect and honour\add* Yahweh and \add ask for\add* \add his\add* favour, and didn’t Yahweh \add relent from sending\add* the disaster that he had pronounced against them? \add It seems that\add* we’re about to bring great \add harm\add* on ourselves.”
\p
\v 20 \add Now\add* there was \add another\add* man prophesying in Yahweh’s name of Yahweh: Uriyah (son of Shemayah from Kiriat-Yearim) who prophesied against this city and against this land \add with similar\add* messages to Yirmeyah.
\v 21 \add When\add* King Yehoyakim \add (Jehoiakim)\add* and all his warriors and all the officials heard his words, the king \add wanted\add* to put him to death. \add However when\add* Uriyah heard \add about it\add*, he became afraid, and he fled and went to Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*.
\v 22 \add However,\add* King Yehoyakim sent sent Akbor’s son Elnatan and several other men to Egypt \add to get Uriyah\add*.
\v 23 They brought Uriyah back from Egypt and took him to King Yehoyakim \add who ran him through with a sword\add* and threw his corpse into the \add public graveyard\add*.
\p
\v 24 However, Shafan’s son Ahikam \add supported\add* Yirmeyah and \add didn’t allow the people to kill him\add*.
\c 27
\s1 Yirmeyah wears a yoke
\p
\v 1 At the beginning of the reign of Yehudah’s King Yehoyakim (\add Jehoiakim\add*, son of Yoshiyah \add Josiah\add*), this message came to Yirmeyah \add (Jeremiah)\add* from Yahweh,\x + \xo 27:1: \xt 2Ki 24:18-20; 2Ch 36:11-13.\x*
\v 2 telling \add him\add* this:
\m Make yourself a wooden \add ox\add* yoke with bars, and \add tie\add* it to your neck.
\v 3 \add Use it to send messages\add* to the kings of Edom, Moab, Ammon, Tsor \add (Tyre)\add*, and Tsidon \add (Sidon)\add*, \add through the ambassadors\add* \add from those countries\add* who’ve come to Yerushalem to \add meet with\add* King Tsidkiyah \add (Zedekiah)\add*
\v 4 to tell them that Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says to give their masters this message:
\v 5 I myself made the earth \add and\add* the \add people\add* and \add animals\add* that are on the earth, by my \add direct actions\add* and my great strength, and I give it to whoever \add see fit\add*.
\v 6 Now I’ve \add personally handed over\add* all these lands to my servant, the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar, and I’ve also given the animals in the countryside to him to serve him.
\v 7 All the nations will serve him and his son and then his \add grandson\add*, until the time of his own land comes \add due\add*. \add Yes, it will\add*, and then many nations and great kings will make him serve them.
\p
\v 8 Any nation or kingdom that won’t serve the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar and that won’t put its neck into his yoke, then I’ll punish that nation with \add war\add* and famine and \add disease\add* until I’ve used \add King Nebuchadnezzar\add* to finish them \add off\add*. That is Yahweh’s declaration,
\v 9 \add so\add* don’t you all keep listening to your ‘prophets’, and to your diviners and dreamers, and to your soothsayers and sorcerers—all those who keep telling you that you all won’t serve the Babylonian king,
\v 10 because they’re prophesying lies to you, so as to remove you all far away from on your land. \add Yes,\add* I will drive you all out and you’ll die \add in a foreign land\add*.
\v 11 \add However,\add* the nation that brings its neck into the Babylonian king’s yoke and serves him, I’ll let \add that nation\add* remain on its land, and it will cultivate it and live \add there\add*. That’s is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 12 Then to Yehudah’s King Tsidkiyah \add (Zedekiah)\add*, I \add passed on\add* those \add same\add* words, saying, “Put your necks into the yoke of the Babylonian king, and serve him and his people, and live.
\v 13 Why would you and your people die from \add war\add*, famine, and \add disease\add*, as Yahweh has \add said will come to any\add* nation that doesn’t serve the Babylonian king?
\v 14 \add So\add* don’t listen to the messages from the prophets who are speaking to you when they tell you all not to serve the king of Babylon as they’re prophesying lies to you
\v 15 because I didn’t send them. Yahweh declares that they’re using my name to prophesy lies so that I’ll drive you out, and you’ll all perish—\add both\add* you and the prophets who are prophesying to you.”
\v 16 Then I told the priests and all those people that Yahweh says: Don’t listen to the words of your prophets who are prophesying to you and saying that the utensils from Yahweh’s \add temple\add* will \add soon\add* be brought back from Babylon, because they’re prophesying lies to you.
\v 17 Don’t listen to them. Serve the Babylonian king and live. Why should this city become a ruin?
\v 18 If they were prophets \add who really have access to\add* Yahweh’s message, then please let them intercede with Commander-in-chief Yahweh so that the utensils remaining in Yahweh’s \add temple\add* and in Yehudah’s king’s \add palace\add* and in Yerushalem \add don’t end up being taken\add* to Babylon.
\p
\v 19 \add Yes,\add* Commander-in-chief Yahweh has spoken about the \add bronze\add* pillars and the \add large, bronze\add* \add water basin\add*, and concerning the \add bronze\add* stands and the rest of the utensils remaining in this city,
\v 20 which the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar didn’t take when he exiled Yehudah’s King Yekonyah (\add Jeconiah,\add* son of \add Yehoyakim/\add*Jehoiakim) from Yerushalem to Babylon, along with all the nobles of Yehudah including Yerushalem.
\v 21 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says about the utensils remaining in Yahweh’s \add temple\add* and in the \add palace\add* of the king of Yehudah and Yerushalem:
\v 22 They’ll be taken to Babylon and they’ll remain there until the \add time when I punish\add* \add those Babylonians\add*, and then I’ll bring them \add back\add* and restore them to this place. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\c 28
\s1 Yirmeyah vs Prophet Hananyah
\p
\v 1 In the fifth month of the fourth year of the reign of Yehudah’s King Tsidkiyah \add (Zedekiah)\add*, Azzur’s son Hananyah who was a ‘prophet’ from Gibeon, said to me in Yahweh’s \add temple\add* as priests and all the people \add watched\add*, saying,\x + \xo 28:1: \xt 2Ki 24:18-20; 2Ch 36:11-13.\x*
\v 2 “Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says: I’ve broken the yoke of the Babylonian king.
\v 3 Within two years, I, myself, will bring back here all the utensils from Yahweh’s residence that the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar got from this place and took to Babylon.
\v 4 I, myself, will \add also\add* bring Yekonyah (\add Jeconiah,\add* the son of Yehudah’s King Yehoyakim/\add Jehoiakim\add*) back to this place, and all the exiles from Yehudah that were taken to Babylon, because I’ll break the yoke of the Babylonian king. That is Yahweh’s declaration.”
\p
\v 5 Then the prophet Yirmeyah spoke to the prophet Hananyah, as the priests and all the people standing in Yahweh’s \add temple\add* \add watched\add*,
\v 6 saying, “Let it be so—may Yahweh do all that. May Yahweh \add confirm\add* your messages that you prophesied, to bring the \add temple utensils\add* back to this place, along with all the exiles from Babylon.
\v 7 However, please listen to this message that I, myself, am speaking \add as you and all the people listen\add*:
\v 8 The prophets who \add preceded\add* \add both\add* me and you, prophesied \add long ago\add* that many \add nations\add* and powerful kingdoms would experience wars, \add terrible suffering\add*, and \add deadly diseases\add*.
\v 9 The prophet who prophesies about peace, \add that\add* prophet will be known as ‘a truthful prophet sent by Yahweh’ \add only\add* when his message comes \add to pass\add*.”
\p
\v 10 Then the prophet Hananyah took the yoke bar off the prophet Yirmeyah’s neck, and broke it.
\v 11 Then as all the people watched, he said, “This is what Yahweh says: Just like that, I’ll break the yoke of the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar off the neck of all the nations within two more years.”
\p Then the prophet Yirmeyah \add left the gathering\add*.
\p
\v 12 After the prophet Hananyah broke the yoke bar that had been on the prophet Yirmeyah’s neck, Yahweh’s message came to Yirmeyah saying,
\v 13 “Go and tell Hananyah this: ‘Yahweh says that you’ve broken wooden yoke bars, but in their place, you’ll make yoke bars out of iron,’
\v 14 because Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says, ‘I’ve put an iron yoke bar on the neck of all these nations to serve the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar, and they will \add indeed\add* serve him. I’ve also given him the animals from the countryside.’ ”
\p
\v 15 Then the prophet Yirmeyah told the prophet Hananyah, “Listen, please, Hananyah. Yahweh hasn’t sent you, and you yourself have made this people \add group\add* \add put their trust in things that aren’t true\add*.
\v 16 Because of that, Yahweh says this: ‘Listen, I’m \add removing you from this world\add*. \add You’ll die this very\add* year, because you have \add said things that would cause the people to rebel\add* against Yahweh.’ ”
\p
\v 17 The prophet Hananyah then died in the seventh month of that year.
\c 29
\s1 Yirmeyah’s letter to the exiled Jews
\p
\v 1 The prophet Yirmeyah sent a \add letter\add* from Yerushalem to the remainder of the elders of the exile, and to the priests, and to the prophets, and to all the people that Nebuchadnezzar had exiled from Yerushalem to Babylon\x + \xo 29:1-2: \xt 2Ki 24:12-16; 2Ch 36:10.\x*
\v 2 after the \add removal\add* from Yerushalem of King Yekonyah \add (Jeconiah)\add* and the queen mother, the \add court officials\add* and the leaders of Yehudah and Yerushalem, plus the craftsmen and the metalsmiths.
\v 3 \add He sent it\add* with Shafan’s son Elasah and Hilkiyah’s son Gemaryah, who Yehudah’s King Tsidkiyah \add (Zedekiah)\add* sent to the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar in Babylon. \add The letter\add* said,
\pi1
\v 4 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this to all \add of you\add* that I’ve exiled from Yerushalem to Babylon:
\v 5 Build houses and live in them, and plant gardens and eat their fruit.
\v 6 \add Marry\add* and \add have children\add*. \add Find\add* wives for your sons and give your daughters \add in marriage\add* so that they \add also\add* \add have children\add*. \add Increase in number\add* there—don’t become fewer.
\v 7 \add In addition, the city that I’ve sent you all into exile to, work to make it more prosperous\add* and pray to Yahweh for it, because \add if it prospers, its prosperity will belong to all of you\add*.
\v 8 That’s because Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this: Don’t let your prophets and diviners who are among you deceive you, and don’t listen to your dreams that you \add wishfully\add* dream,
\v 9 because \add those prophets\add* are prophesying \add using\add* my name \add but not being truthful\add*—I didn’t send them. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 10 “Because this is what Yahweh says: When seventy years \add have passed\add* for Babylon, I’ll visit \add take notice of you all\add* \add again\add*, and I’ll \add implement\add* my good message about you—to bring you all back to this place,\x + \xo 29:10: \xt 2Ch 36:21; Jer 25:11; Dan 9:2.\x*
\v 11 because I know the plans that I \add have\add* for you all: plans for peaceful well-being—not to bring you all harm, \add but rather\add* a future \add with\add* hope. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\v 12 Then you’ll all call out to me \add for help\add*, and you’ll come and pray to me, and I’ll listen to you all.
\v 13 You’ll search for me, and you’ll find me, because you’ll all \add want to follow me with complete sincerity\add*.\x + \xo 29:13: \xt Deu 4:29.\x*
\v 14 Then, Yahweh has declared, I’ll let myself be found by you all, and I’ll \add bring you back from\add* captivity. I’ll gather you all from all the nations and all the places that I banished you to, and I’ll bring you all back to the place that I sent you into exile from. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\pi1
\v 15 Because you’ve all said that Yahweh has \add appointed\add* prophets for \add you\add* \add there\add* in Babylon,
\v 16 \add then\add* Yahweh \add has something to say\add* about the king sitting on David’s throne and about all the people living in this city—your relatives who didn’t go into exile with you.
\v 17 So Commander-in-chief Yahweh says: Listen, I’m about to send \add war\add*, famine and \add deadly diseases\add* against them. I’ll make them like rotten figs that are so bad they’re \add inedible\add*.
\v 18 \add Yes,\add* I’ll chase after them with \add war\add*, famine, and \add deadly diseases\add*, and I’ll make them become a horror to all the \add world’s\add* kingdoms—a curse and a desolation, and a reproach and \add something to be hissed at\add* by all the nations where I’ve driven them,
\v 19 because they didn’t listen to my messages that I sent to them \add over and over again\add* via my servants the prophets, but all you \add exiles\add* didn’t listen. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 20 \add But\add* all you exiles that I sent away from Yerushalem to Babylon, listen to Yahweh’s message:
\pi1
\v 21 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh, says this about Kolayah’s son Ahav and Maaseyah’s son Tsidkiyah, who are \add both\add* prophesying untruths to you in my name: Listen, I’m \add handing them over\add* to the Babylonian King Nebuchadnezzar, and he’ll \add kill them right in front of you\add*.
\v 22 Then because of them, a \add new\add* curse \add phrase\add* will be taken on by all the \add Jewish\add* exiles in Babylon, which goes, “May Yahweh make you like Tsidkiyah and Ahav, who were roasted in the fire by the Babylonian king,”
\v 23 because they did something shameful in Yisrael and they have committed adultery with the wives of their neighbours, and they spoke untrue messages in my name that I hadn’t commanded them to. I am the one \add who knows that\add* and I’m a witness. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\s1 Message to false prophet Shemayah
\p
\v 24 \add Yahweh told me to\add* tell Shemayah (the Nehelamite) this:
\v 25 Yisrael’s god, Commander-in-chief Yahweh says this: Because you sent letters in your name to all the people in Yerushalem, and to the priest Tsefanyah (Maaseyah’s son), and to all the priests, to tell \add Tsefanyah\add*:
\pi1
\v 26 Yahweh has made you, \add Tsefanyah,\add* priest in place of the priest Yehoyada \add (Jehoiada)\add*, to be \add overseer\add* in Yahweh’s \add temple\add* over every man who raves \add out loud\add*, making himself a prophet, and you must put him in the stocks \add with an iron collar around his\add* neck.
\v 27 \add So why\add* haven’t you rebuked Yirmeyah the Antotite who’s prophesying to you all,
\v 28 because he’s sent \add a letter\add* to us \add here\add* in Babylon saying, “\add Your exile\add* \add will last a long time\add*. Build houses and live in them. Plant gardens and eat their fruit.”
\p
\v 29 The priest Tsefanyah read that letter to the prophet Yirmeyah,
\v 30 then Yahweh \add gave\add* this message to Yirmeyah:
\v 31 Send to all the \add exiles\add* to tell them: This is what Yahweh says about Shemayah the Nehelamite: Because Shemayah has prophesied to you all, \add even though\add* I didn’t send him, and he made you trust \add what’s not true\add*,
\v 32 therefore Yahweh says this: Listen, I \add will punish\add* Shemayah the Nehelamite and \add his descendants\add*. \add None of his family\add* will live among this people, and \add he won’t experience the good things\add* that I’ll do for my people, because he’s \add encouraged\add* rebellion against Yahweh. That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\c 30
\s1 Yahweh’s promises to his people
\p
\v 1 Yahweh \add gave\add* Yirmeyah a message, saying:
\v 2 Yisrael’s god, Yahweh says this: Write down on a scroll all the messages that I’ve \add given\add* you,
\v 3 because listen to Yahweh’s declaration: The \add time\add* is coming when I’ll restore my people of Yisrael and Yehudah from captivity, and I’ll bring them back to the land that I have to their ancestors, and they’ll \add take possession of it\add* \add again\add*.
\p
\v 4 \add Now\add* these are the messages that Yahweh spoke concerning Yisrael and Yehudah:
\q1
\v 5 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh says this:
\q1 A \add cry of panic and terror\add* has been heard,
\q1 and there’s no peace.
\q1
\v 6 Please ask and \add find out\add*: can \add males\add* give birth?
\q1 Why do I see every strong man with his hands on his \add hips\add* like a woman \add in labour\add*?
\q1 And \add why has\add* \add everyone’s faces gone so pale\add*?
\q1
\v 7 Oh dear, \add that will be a terrible day like nothing that’s come before\add*.
\q1 It’ll be a distressing time for Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*,
\q1 →\add but\add* he’ll be rescued from it.
\p
\v 8 Then Commander-in-chief Yahweh declares that \add at that time\add* I’ll break his yoke off your neck, and I’ll \add pull\add* your \add chains\add* apart, and foreigners will no longer enslave \add your country\add*.
\v 9 Then they’ll serve their god Yahweh, and their king \add on David’s throne\add* who I’ll appoint for them.
\p
\v 10 Then Yahweh declares:
\q1 Then you, my servant Yakov \add (Jacob)\add*, don’t be afraid,
\q1 and don’t be dismayed, Yisrael \add (Israel)\add*,
\q1 because listen, I’m rescuing you from afar,
\q1 and your offspring from the land \add where they were held captive\add*.
\q1 \add Yisrael\add* will return and be left alone and at ease,
\q1 and there won’t be anyone making it afraid.\x + \xo 30:10-11: \xt Jer 46:27-28.\x*
\q1
\v 11 Yahweh declares:
\q1 \add Yes,\add* I’m with you to rescue you,
\q1 because I’ll \add completely destroy\add* all the nations that I’ve scattered you to,
\q1 but I won’t \add completely destroy\add* you.
\q1 I’ll discipline you according to justice,
\q1 \add but I won’t just let you off what you deserve\add*.
\p
\v 12 \add Yes,\add* Yahweh says this:
\q1 Your fracture is incurable.
\q1 Your wound is severe.
\q1
\v 13 There’s no one pleading your cause.
\q1 There’s no medicines for your wound.
\q1 There’s no healing for you.
\q1
\v 14 All your lovers have forgotten you—
\q1 they don’t care about you.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* I’ve struck you \add like an enemy would\add*,
\q1 with the discipline of a cruel \add person\add*,
\q1 due to the \add severity of your wickedness\add*.
\q1 You’ve \add disobeyed so frequently\add*.
\q1
\v 15 Why do you cry out about your fracture—
\q1 about your incurable pain?
\q1 Your \add wickedness has been severe\add*.
\q1 You’ve \add disobeyed so often\add*
\q1 →\add so\add* I’ve done those things to you.
\q1
\v 16 \add Because of that\add*, all those who devoured you will be devoured,
\q1 and all of your adversaries, every one of them, will go into captivity.
\q1 Then the ones plundering you will become like plunder,
\q1 and all those preying on you, I’ll give \add to you\add* as spoil.
\q1
\v 17 \add Yes,\add* I’ll bring healing to you,
\q1 and I’ll heal you from your wounds
\q1 because they’ve called you an outcast.
\q1 ‘She is Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*—no one cares about her.’
\q1 That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\p
\v 18 Yahweh says this:
\q1 Listen, I’m restoring the fortune of Yakov’s \add (Jacob’s)\add* \add descendants\add*,
\q1 and I will have compassion on \add the places where they live\add*.
\q1 \add Each\add* city will be rebuilt on its mound,
\q1 and \add each\add* fortress will sit on its proper place.
\q1
\v 19 Then thanksgiving will go out from them,
\q1 and the sound of those laughing.
\q1 I’ll multiply them, and they won’t diminish \add in number\add*,
\q1 →and I’ll make them honoured—
\q1 they won’t become insignificant.
\q1
\v 20 Then its children will be as in \add former times\add*,
\q1 and its community will be established \add under my supervision\add*,
\q1 and I’ll punish \add all those who oppress it\add*.
\q1
\v 21 Its \add king\add* will be from among it,
\q1 and its ruler will come from its middle.
\q1 Then I’ll bring it near, and it will approach me,
\q1 because who is this that has pledged its heart to approach me?
\m That is Yahweh’s declaration.
\q1
\v 22 You’ll be my people
\q1 and I’ll become your god.
\p
\v 23 Listen, Yahweh’s storm of rage has gone out—
\q1 a storm whirling around the \add heads\add* of wicked \add people\add*.
\q1
\v 24 Yahweh’s burning \add anger\add* won’t turn back
\q1 until he’s established and \add completed what he’s planned\add*.
\q1 You’ll all understand it in the days \add to come\add*.
\c 31
\s1 Yisrael’s return home
\p
\v 1 Yahweh declares that at that time, I’ll be \add the\add* god to all of Yisrael’s \add families\add*, and they’ll be my people.
\v 2 Yahweh says this:
\q1 A people, the survivors \add after being attacked in war\add*,
\q1 found favour in the wilderness,
\q1 Yisrael going to find \add a peaceful place\add*.
\q1
\v 3 From far off, Yahweh appeared to me: I’ve always loved you
\q1 therefore I’ve \add displayed\add* loyal commitment \add to help you endure\add*.
\q1
\v 4 I’ll rebuild you, and you’ll be \add restored\add*, Yisrael’s \add pretty daughter\add*.
\q1 Again you’ll adorn yourself with your tambourines,
\q1 and will go out in the dance of \add those celebrating\add*.
\q1
\v 5 You’ll plant vineyards again on the Shomron \add (Samaria)\add* hills.
\q1 The planters will plant and \add make them productive\add*.
\q1
\v 6 \add Yes,\add* there’ll be a day when the watchers in the Efrayim hill country will call out,
\q1 ‘\add Get ready\add* and let’s go up to our god Yahweh at Tsiyyon \add (Zion)\add*,’
\q1
\v 7 because Yahweh says this:
\q1 “Sing for \add Yisrael\add* (Yakov) with gladness,
\q1 and shout for this \add leader\add* of the nations.
\q1 Cause it to be heard, praise, and say,
\q1 ‘Yahweh, save your people, the remnant of Yisrael.’
\q1
\v 8 Listen, I’m bringing them \add back\add* from the land in the north,
\q1 and I’ll gather them from the remote parts of the \add world\add*.
\q1 Among them are the blind and the lame,
\q1 and pregnant \add women\add* together with those giving birth.
\q1 A \add large number of people\add* will return here.
\q1
\v 9 \add They’ll be weeping as\add* they come,
\q1 and \add as they request me\add*, I’ll bring them \add out\add*.
\q1 I’ll cause them to walk to streams of water on a straight road.
\q1 They won’t stumble on it.
\q1 because I’ve become a father for Yisrael,
\q1 and Efrayim,\f + \fr 31:9 \ft As a synonym, also referring to Yisrael.\f* he’s my firstborn.
\p
\v 10 \add Listen to\add* Yahweh’s message, \add you\add* nations,
\q1 and declare it in the coastlands from far off, and say,
\q1 ‘The one scattering Yisrael will gather him \add back\add*,
\q1 and he’ll protect him like a shepherd of his flock,
\q1
\v 11 because Yahweh has ransomed \add Yisrael\add* (Yakov)
\q1 and \add paid the price to free\add* it from the \add power\add* of a \add nation that’s\add* stronger than it.
\q1
\v 12 Then they’ll come and sing on Tsiyyon’s \add (Zion’s)\add* heights,
\q1 and they’ll be radiant about Yahweh’s goodness:
\q1 about the grain, about the new wine and the fresh oil,
\q1 and about the young from the flock and the herd.
\q1 Their soul will be like a watered garden,
\q1 and they won’t \add be weakened\add* again.
\q1
